# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banff-springs-hotel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] King George VI and Queen Elizabeth made their visit to Canada from 17 May to 15 June 1939.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Taking place in the months leading up to the Second World War, the tour was undertaken to strengthen trans-Atlantic support for the United Kingdom in anticipation of a potential war while also showcasing Canada's status as an independent Dominion of the British Empire.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen arrived in Canada by ship, and travelled up the St.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Lawrence River to Quebec City before heading west by rail.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Accompanied throughout by Canadian Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, they visited most major cities across Canada, reaching as far west as Victoria, British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On their return journey east, they briefly travelled to the United States for a state visit and a meeting with President Franklin D.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal tour concluded with visits to the Maritimes, after which they departed from Halifax for a tour of the then separate Dominion of Newfoundland.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Although royal family members had previously toured Canada, the 1939 royal tour marked the first time a reigning monarch of Canada visited North America, garnering significant attention from both the public and the media.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Elizabeth's mother had died in 1938, and so Norman Hartnell designed an all-white wardrobe for her delayed state visit to France that year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] In Canada in 1939 she wore elements of this white mourning, which forms a distinctive feature of the black and white photographs of the tour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The first portion of the royal tour occurred from 17 May 1939, when the royal couple arrived in Quebec City, to 7 June 1939, when George VI and Mackenzie King departed Canada to conduct a state visit to the United States.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The first portion of the Canadian royal tour, saw the royal couple visit every province in Canada, excluding the provinces in Atlantic Canada, which was toured following George VI and Mackenzie King's return from the United States on 12 June.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The king and queen took up residence at La Citadelle, where the King performed his first official tasks, amongst which was the acceptance of the credentials of Daniel Calhoun Roper as the American envoy to Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King also held the audience with Quebeckers in the Legislative Council chamber of the Parliament Building.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal party traveled to Ottawa on 20 May, where the Queen laid the cornerstone of the Supreme Court building.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] There, the King personally granted royal assent to nine bills in the traditional manner which was still being used in Canada at the time – in the United Kingdom, Royal Assent has not been granted by the Sovereign in person since 1854.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On Parliament Hill, the King's official Canadian birthday (known today as Victoria Day) was marked for the first time with a traditional Trooping of the Colour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Because he attended this parade instead of the annual trooping on Horse Guards Parade, the one in London was presided by Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Queen Elizabeth and Governor General Lord Tweedsmuir watched the parade from East Block.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King was accompanied at the reviewing box by Prime Minister Mackenzie King, Minister of National Defence Ian Alistair Mackenzie and the Chief of the General Staff, Lieutenant General Ernest Charles Ashton.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The trooping saw members of the Governor General's Foot Guards from Ottawa and the Canadian Grenadier Guards from Montreal, both of which make up the Brigade of Canadian Guards, parade before the King.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After two days in Ottawa, the royal couple began travelling westward.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple travelled to Toronto on 22 May, where they attended the King's Plate horse race and dedicated Coronation Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple dedicated the soon-to-be completed Rainbow Bridge at Niagara Falls, and unveiled a monument at the site to mark the occasion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] They also inaugurated the Queen Elizabeth Way (which was named for George's royal consort) as well as various monuments along the route, including a set of decorative stone pillars on the eastern approach to the Henley Bridge in St.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The Royal Train was operated by the Canadian Pacific Railway on the western leg of the tour and the couple continued to be greeted by throngs of Canadians, even in the immigrant-rich but Depression-battered Prairies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple visited Winnipeg and Brandon on 24 May.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] While staying at Government House in Winnipeg, the King made his longest-ever radio broadcast to the British Empire; the table at which he sat remains in the Aides Room of the royal residence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Then, Prime Minister Mackenzie King described the arrival of the royal train at Brandon: "Wonderful cheering.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] A long bridge overhead crowded with people.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Continuing westward across the Prairies, the Royal Train arrived in Regina on 25 May, followed by Calgary on 26 May and Banff on 27 May.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After some conventional compliments on the turnout of the escort, the King had said that he had not expected either such crowds or a ceremonial military welcome.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] When he had asked Mackenzie King what to expect in Calgary, the Prime Minister has said it was only a small place of little consequence and that there would not be much there.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] When he saw the guard of honour waiting on the platform, he realized that he should have been in uniform and went back inside the train.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] But it was, of course, too late to change.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] (Major) Bradbrooke got the impression that the King was not at all pleased with his Canadian Prime Minister's advice that day.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] In Banff, Their Majesties and Mackenzie King posed for press photographs at the Banff Springs Hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen also attended a private service at St George-in-the-Pines Anglican church.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and the Queen stopped in Vancouver, Victoria, and a number of other smaller communities in British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Mackenzie King was enthused, stating in his diary on 29 May 1939, "the day in Vancouver was one of the finest on the entire tour," and, the following day: "Without question, Victoria has left the most pleasing of all impressions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] At one night time stop in the Rocky Mountains, the royal couple sang along with an impromptu a cappella rendition of "When the Moon Comes over the Mountain" that broke out amongst the gathered crowd when the moon emerged from behind the clouds.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal train arrived in the town of Melville at 10 pm on 3 June, attracting over 60,000 people to the town of 3,000.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The stop was meant to last only ten minutes, after which the train would stay overnight for servicing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] But, with the throngs of people who arrived, the royal party decided to extend the visit to a half-hour, after which the train pulled away, returning a few hours later, once the crowds had dispersed; Canadian Press reporter R.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Another factor, however, was public relations; the presence of the King and Queen, in both Canada and the United States, was calculated to shore up sympathy for Britain in anticipation of hostilities with Nazi Germany.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The itinerary included visits to Mount Vernon on 9 June, the 1939 New York World's Fair on 10 June, and dinner at Roosevelt's estate at Hyde Park on 11 June, at which President Roosevelt served hot dogs, smoked turkey, and strawberry shortcake to the royal couple.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The 2012 film *Hyde Park on Hudson* starring Bill Murray contains a lengthy fictionalized depiction of the royal couple's visit to the Roosevelt estate.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On 12 June the royal couple returned to Canada to continue their royal tour of the country, visiting the Maritime provinces.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and the Queen stopped in Doaktown, New Brunswick, to take tea in a local tearoom.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] While they were expected for lunch, they were not expected in the kitchen afterwards, and they took the staff by surprise.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After a visit to Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, the royal couple ended their tour at Halifax, Nova Scotia, on 15 June, where a farewell luncheon was held, and the King and Queen each delivered a speech of thanks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] She was accompanied by British warships and our own destroyers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The *Bluenose* and other vessels also in the harbour as a sort of escort....
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen were at the very top of the ship and kept waving....
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] John's, Newfoundland, George VI and Elizabeth returned to the United Kingdom.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Elizabeth told Canadian Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, "that tour made us", and she returned to Canada frequently both on official tours and privately.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] During another tour of Canada in 1985, Queen Elizabeth, by then the Queen Mother, said, "it is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] For the visit the Canadian government issued its second commemorative silver dollar, this one showing the standard picture of the king on the obverse and the Canadian Parliament building on the reverse.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] With a mintage of 1,363,816—large for the time—it remains readily available.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] At the same time a set of three postage stamps were issued by Canada, two showing members of the Royal Family and one a war memorial.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The **1988 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XV Olympic Winter Games** (French: *XVes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Calgary 1988** were a multi-sport event held from February 13 to 28, 1988, with Calgary, Alberta, as the main host city.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This marks the most recent time that two consecutive Olympic Games were hosted in North America (with the 1984 Summer Olympic Games hosted in Los Angeles, California, United States).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to be held for 15 days, like the counterpart Summer Olympic Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The majority of the events took place in Calgary itself.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the snow events were shared by Nakiska ski resort in Kananaskis Country at the west of the city and the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park in the town of Canmore.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the last Winter Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1988, a record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOC) sent a total of 1,424 athletes to these Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These Winter Olympics would be the last attended for both the Soviet Union and East Germany NOCs.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Just like the 1976 Summer Olympics, host country Canada failed again to win a gold medal on their home soil (they won three gold medals in demonstration events, but these are not included in the official medal table).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Finnish ski jumper, Matti Nykänen, and the Dutch speed skater, Yvonne van Gennip, won three individual gold medals each.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics were also remembered for the "heroic failure" of both the British ski jumper, Michael Edwards, and the debut of the Jamaica national bobsleigh team.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Both of them became subjects of major feature films about their participation in these Games: *Cool Runnings* by Walt Disney Pictures in 1993 and *Eddie the Eagle* by 20th Century Fox in 2016.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At approximately C$829 million, the Calgary Games were the most expensive Olympics ever held at the time, as all the necessary infrastructure was built from scratch.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The facilities that were built for these Winter Olympics helped the host region to turn into the heart of Canada's elite winter sports program, under the tutelage of WinSport.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the Games, their legacy still standing and in constant use, as the five purpose-built venues for those Games are now used for training and hosting various winter sporting events every year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These policies helped Canada develop into one of the top nations in Winter Olympics competition.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The climax of this effort was the overall first-place finish at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary made its fourth attempt at hosting the Winter Games when it bid for the 1988 Winter Olympic Games, which also marked Canada's seventh bid for the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Montreal made the first Canadian bid for the Winter Games in 1956 and won the rights to host the 1976 Summer Olympics, and Vancouver made attempts to host the 1976 and 1980 Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary, alongside neighbouring Banff, under the leadership of the Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA), submitted bids for the Winter Games in 1964, 1968, and 1972.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, CODA went dormant in 1966 after losing three consecutive bids.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, Frank King and Bob Niven of Calgary's Booster Club took over the organization's leadership and revived CODA.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King and Niven consulted former Olympic Sprinter and CODA founder, Ernie McCullough, and politician Arthur Ryan Smith, who had worked on previous bids, for guidance on the project.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In October 1979, CODA secured the Canadian Olympic Association's (COA) support for Canada's official bid to host the 1988 Winter Olympics, winning over a competing bid by Vancouver with a vote of 27–9.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary's bid was at the time the most ambitious for the Winter Olympics ever, as the city lacked winter sports facilities and almost everything would have to be built from scratch.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA proposed constructing all new venues, arguing that if Calgary was awarded the Games, Canada's inventory of training facilities would increase significantly.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Vancouver bidding committee argued that Calgary's bid represented a "Big-ticket Games" idea, and estimated to cost nearly three times what Vancouver was expected to pay to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Vancouver's bid was based on already developed infrastructure, including the Expo 86 precinct, the Pacific Coliseum and Whistler Blackcomb, which later served as the basis for the successful 2010 Winter Olympics bid and the later unsuccessful 2030 Winter Olympics bid.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA then spent two years building local support for the megaproject, selling CA$5 memberships to approximately 80,000 of Calgary's 600,000 residents.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary also secured CA$270 million in funding from the federal (CA$200 million) and provincial governments.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Some civic leaders, including then-mayor Ralph Klein, travelled around the world to lobby IOC delegates.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The arrival of the National Hockey League's (NHL) newly relocated Calgary Flames from Atlanta in 1980 drove the city to construct a new multi-use arena that would later be named the Olympic Saddledome, demonstrating to the IOC Calgary's determination to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic bid itself emphasized the unique cultural and natural characteristics who mark the Calgary Metropolitan Region and the Alberta Province and also canadian prairies landscapes, as a perfect places for hosting the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At the bidding documents, the city was marketed with a capitalist, oil-driven and vibrant economy that also had mountain playgrounds, extensive wilderness, and a rodeo culture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When the two images of Calgary and Alberta were brought together, they seemed to be contrasting; however, they complemented each other as part of extensive and intense bidding lobby process.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary was one of three finalists during the 1988 Winter Olympics bid process.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The other two were Falun, Sweden, and Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Italian town (comune) had before hosted the 1956 Winter Olympics and was seen by many as the favorite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The vote was held on September 30, 1981, in Baden-Baden, West Germany, during the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After Cortina d'Ampezzo was eliminated in the first round of balloting, Calgary won in the second and final round of balloting over Falun, by a margin of 17 votes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The announcement of CODA's victory sent the delegates in Baden-Baden and Calgary residents into singing and dancing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also made then Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, burst openly into tears in front of the cameras.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Later, Ralph Klein sang a rendition of Mac Davis' *It's Hard to Be Humble*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympics awarded to Canada and the second Olympic Games overall, following the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Cortina d'Ampezzo, along with Milan, would get to host the 2026 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pelle noted that once the Games were awarded to Calgary, the cultural and community aspects of the bid were pushed aside by the newly formed Calgary Olympic organizing committee called the *Olympiques Calgary Olympics '88* (OCO'88).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It then proceeded to take on a "vigorous, resilient, and impersonal corporate business strategy" based in the work made by Los Angeles 1984 Organizing Committee (LAOCOG) toward the planning and operation of the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Bill Pratt was a former general contractor who took over as OCO'88 president in 1983.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He was the main manager that oversaw the construction of the Olympic megaproject.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Donald Jacques, a former general manager of the Calgary Exhibition and Stampede, once said, "Because of him, everything was built on time and on budget." However, Bill Pratt was controversial by rubbing many of his colleagues the wrong way.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One former co-worker once predicted back in 1983: "He will get everything built.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There may not be many (of us) left around to enjoy it, but he'll get it done." His relations with the news media were also strained at times.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He had barely settled into his new position when the Calgary press media began criticizing OCO'88 for excessive secrecy and for awarding Olympic contracts to Calgary's PR firm Francis Williams and Johnson Ltd.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pratt was a director of that firm, before accepting the organizing committee job.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 had insisted that there was no conflict of interest involved in the whole process.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Pratt declared: "I have been nailed for a lot, but that does not bother me.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the 1988 Winter Olympics bid was won in 1981, OCO'88 made a new technical assessment and had to re-plan all the originally proposed competition venues except for the few that already existed and were within the campus of the University of Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] McMahon Stadium, the primary outdoor facility used mainly by the Canadian Football League's (CFL) Calgary Stampeders and inside of the University of Calgary and had originally been chosen to host only the opening ceremonies and the Saddledome was chosen to be the place of the closing ceremonies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] But with the constant revisions of the project, the later addition of 4 more days in competition and mainly the gigantic demands for tickets, the Organizing Committee decided to move the closing ceremony to the Stadium which held twice the capacity of the Saddledome.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The last time that the two Winter Olympic ceremonies were held at the same venue was at the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley, California.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics' five main all-purpose venues were created at a significant cost at that time.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three of them are located within Calgary and the other two are located west of the city.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Olympic Saddledome was planned to be the main venue of the games, hosting ice hockey and figure skating finals.This arena is also part of Stampede Park and was expected to cost C$83 million, but a cost overrun pushed it to nearly C$100 million and caused a nine-month delay.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Second, the Olympic Oval was built on the campus of the University of Calgary for C$40 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Third, Canada Olympic Park (formerly called the *Paskapoo Ski Hill*) was renovated for C$200 million and is located on the western outskirts of Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This most expensive venue of these Winter Olympics hosted the men's bobsleigh, luge, and men's ski jumping and its portion of the Nordic combined events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, it hosted some events of the demonstration sport of freestyle skiing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From the west of Calgary, the other two main all-purpose venues were built at the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Canmore Nordic Centre was 90% funded by the province of Alberta, for C$17.3 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located beside the town of Canmore and it hosted cross-country skiing, plus its men's portion of the Nordic combined, and the men's biathlon events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was projected that the area could become a year-round destination for Albertans, by facilitating and accelerate Canmore's economic transition away from coal mining to tourist attraction.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the Nakiska (*Cree* meaning "to meet") ski resort was the most controversial and polemic complex built for these Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located on Mount Allan (inside Kananaskis Country) and it hosted the alpine skiing events.It cost around C$25 million to Alberta government funds.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This venue drew a lot of criticisms because of the various environmental concerns, the rejection by International Ski Federation (FIS) of slopes for each of the 10 events in the program and the use of artificial snow due to the lack of natural snow on that season.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the first inspections, the International Ski Federation (FIS) officials noted the venue's lack of technical difficulties needed for the Olympic competition.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, these FIS delegates proposed some major changes in the slopes in an action to cause bigger difficulties.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These modifications were met with praise from Olympic alpine skiing competitors.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Like at Canada Olympic Park, this venue also hosted some freestyle skiing events as a demonstration sport.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three other existing facilities served as secondary competition venues for the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The first one, was the Max Bell Centre hosted the demonstration sports of curling and short track speed skating.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Father David Bauer Olympic Arena and the Stampede Corral shared the functions of secondary venues for the ice hockey tournament and the figure skating preliminaries.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Though the Stampede Corral did not support the International Ice Hockey Federation's (IIHF) standard-sized Olympic ice surface, OCO'88 was able to convince the IIHF to sanction the ice rink for Olympic competition, in exchange for a C$1.2 million payment.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) entered athletes at the 1988 Winter Olympics, with eight more NOCs than any other previous Olympic Winter Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] 1,109 men and 315 women, for a total of 1,424 athletes, participated in these Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Fiji, Guam, Guatemala, Jamaica, the Netherlands Antilles and the Virgin Islands had their Winter Olympics debut in 1988.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There were 46 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, there were 22 events in 4 demonstration sports and disciplines that have no official status in the overall medal tally.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather conditions were a problem facing OCO'88 during the Games, with temperatures ranging from −28 to 22 °C (−18 to 72 °F).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After an unexpectedly freezing opening ceremony, the outdoor competitions scheduled to start the next day had to be postponed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This ended up affecting the men's downhill skiing event at Nakiska which was postponed for one day, due to Chinook winds blowing up to 160 km/h.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The women's downhill event also experienced the same scenario.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] With the ski jumping venue facing north at Canada Olympic Park (COP), the same winds also disrupted those events, with the large hill event being postponed four times.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also disrupted the Nordic combined events, in which the ski jumping part had to be postponed as well.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This situation ended up causing something unprecedented in the history of the Winter Olympics, as for the first time both the ski jumping and Nordic combined cross-country skiing events were contested in a single day.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite using artificial cooling, the bobsleigh and luge events did not need to be rescheduled; however, several races had to be postponed because of the high temperatures recorded and also because of the dirt that was carried away by these winds.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA) Board of Directors had originally 25 members.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was chaired by Frank King, followed by former Mayors Ralph Klein and Ross Alger, and other prominent Calgarians.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The executive committee president was Robert Niven.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Organizing Committee (OOC) was formed by utilizing many of the original board of directors members.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was initially started with 11 members and was grown to 25 members by October 1983.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It grew further to 29 members by 1985, when former Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, was added to the list.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] An Olympic biographer, Kevin Wamsley, noted that the CEO Frank King, President Bill Pratt, Ralph Klein, and former COA President Roger Jackson had collectively the most influence on all aspects of these Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This organizing committee took a hierarchical form for planning these Olympics, which caused consternation from some staff, volunteers, and people in executive roles.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The original staff, who were at odds with the current management structure, were either fired or willingly resigned.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, there were claims that some of the volunteers were verbally abused.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As a result, David Leighton resigned as OOC President in 1982, after only five months on the job.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Bill Pratt, a former general manager of the Calgary Stampede, became the new OCOG's president shortly afterwards.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The City of Calgary and the Canadian Olympic Association (COA) delegated officially all Olympic responsibilities, including staging the Winter Olympics under the Olympic Charter, to the newly formed OCO'88 in February and September 1983 respectively.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, conflicts within OCO'88 grew in the public eye and a review of the entire management structure was conducted after Ralph Klein threatened it with a public inquiry in 1986.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Thus, Frank King remained as CEO, but with the addition of more full-time staff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, more than 9,000 volunteers were registered who were allocated to the most diverse areas.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite these changes, there was still some animosity within OCO'88.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Kevin Walmsley noted that Bill Pratt and Frank King continued to have a very tense relationship and that any movement caused sparks with each other.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games coincided with a shift in television policy by the International Olympic Committee and growing enthusiasm by broadcasters in the United States.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Amendments to the *Olympic Charter* in 1977 established a policy mandating joint television rights involving the IOC and the local organizing committee and was enshrined in the 1981 bid agreement for the Calgary games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The joint negotiating committee convened in 1984 late-January, some weeks before the Sarajevo 1984 Winter Games at the IOC's president residency at the Lausanne Palace were held to negotiate the Calgary television contracts with American broadcasters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiating committee was represented by Dick Pound for the IOC, Bill Wardle for OCO'88 and consultant Barry Frank.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The co-negotiating committee designed a new tender process for the television rights bid with an emphasis on creating a level playing field for all broadcasters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time, the negotiations were based on a series of sealed bids and representatives from ABC, CBS and NBC vied for the opportunity to broadcast the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After six rounds of sealed bids, the ABC delegation led by producer Roone Arledge was successful with an agreement paying a record US$309 million (CA$386 million Canadian at the time) in exchange for exclusive rights for the games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CBS exited the bidding process after the second round with a final offer of $257 million, while ABC and NBC both reached the fifth round with an offer of $300 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the sixth and final stage, the IOC and OCO'88 decided a coin flip would determine which of ABC or NBC had the right to submit the first bid or defer, a decision neither network supported.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Watson elected to call the coin-flip, although he remained silent on the first flip, so a second coinflip was required, and NBC won with a choice of "heads", and after 30 minutes of deliberation submitted a $304 million bid.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's representative Arledge made a quick phone call to executive Fred Pierce, and ABC submitted a $309 million bid, exceeding NBC's bid by $5 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's record-setting bid was immediately controversial, first Arledge had exceeded the maximum allowable bid set by ABC's executives by $34 million, and in the coming weeks ABC's coverage of the 1984 Winter Olympics which cost $91.5 million returned poor Nielsen ratings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Early estimates speculated the network would lose $50-$60 million televising the games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* described the NBC agreement as the "biggest prize of the Winter Olympics".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The deal which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a sporting event, allowed OCO'88 to announce the Games would be debt-free.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiations with American television broadcasters were in sharp contrast to negotiations for Western European rights with the European Broadcasting Union quickly closing an exclusive deal with the IOC for US$5.7 million led by Juan Antonio Samaranch and Marc Hodler on behalf of the IOC.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The *Calgary Herald* headline after the announcement negatively reflected on the "bargain" the European network received, and OCO'88 chairman Frank King publicly expressed his disappointment with the IOC.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Samaranch's argument for providing for a privileged negotiation with EBU was ensuring European viewers had equal access and coverage of the games, something he did not believe would occur if private networks from each nation were provided with the opportunity to bid.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dick Pound was also critical of the decision and argued more revenue could be brought in from BBC and RAI alone and the privileged status suppressed the willingness of the EBU to make a market-value bid on the games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CTV Television Network won the bid to broadcast the Games in Canada in December 1983, paying CA$4.5 million for the exclusive rights.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CTV also won the $23.5 million contract to serve as the host broadcaster, responsible for the manpower and equipment to televise the games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, while the bid was strengthened, CBC and CTV signed an agreement that if Calgary were the eventual winner, the two broadcasters would create a consortium in which the purchase of television rights would take place jointly.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The previous arrangement had CBC provide full coverage for Summer Games with CTV broadcasting a nightly summary, while CTV had the rights to Winter Games with CBC broadcasting a nightly summary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The nightly summary of the Games was also televised on CBC.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Japan's broadcast rights were awarded to NHK in July 1986 for US$3.9 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 made several alterations to the Olympic program as part of efforts to ensure value for its broadcast partners.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Now, the premier and main events, including ice hockey and figure skating, were scheduled for prime time and the Games were lengthened to 15 days from the previous 12 to ensure three weekends of coverage.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, a significant downturn in advertising revenue for sporting events resulted in ABC forecasting significant financial losses on the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary organizers appreciated their fortunate timing in signing the deal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King described the timing of the contract with ABC as "the passing of the sun and the moon at the right time for Calgary".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The revenue growth from broadcasting was significant for the Calgary Games, OCO'88 generated $324.9 million in broadcast rights, which was a significant growth over an eight-period (the 1980 Lake Placid Games generated US$20.7 million).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC had net losses of more than $60 million, and broadcast rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics were later sold to the CBS network for $243 million, a 20 per cent reduction compared to Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A series of ticket-related scandals plagued the organizing committee as the Games approached, resulting in widespread public anger.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Demand for tickets was high, particularly for the main events which had sold out a year in advance.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Residents had been promised that only 10 per cent of tickets would go to "Olympic insiders", IOC officials and sponsors, but OCO'88 was later forced to admit that up to 50 percent of seats to top events had gone to insiders.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee, which was subsequently chastised by mayor Klein for running a "closed shop", admitted that it had failed to properly communicate the obligations it had to supply IOC officials and sponsors with priority tickets.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At that time, the American dollar was trading 40 cents higher than the Canadian dollar, resulting in significantly higher than anticipated revenue through currency conversion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The ticket manager maintained his innocence claiming he was used as a scapegoat and sponsor credit card Visa was responsible for the error, despite his claims, the ticketing manager was convicted of fraud, theft, and forgery, and sentenced to 5 years in prison.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Organizers attempted to respond to public concern by asking sponsors to consider reducing their orders and by paying $1.5 million to add 2,600 seats to the Saddledome, as well as increase capacity for ski jumping, alpine skiing and the opening ceremonies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This led to a change of the venue of the closing ceremonies from Saddledome to McMahon Stadium, as the stadium capacity was about two times bigger than the indoor venue.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King also noted that the Calgary Games offered a then-record 1.9 million tickets for sale, three times the amount available at Sarajevo or Lake Placid and that 79 percent of them were to be allocated to Calgarians.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] By the start of the 1988 Winter Games, a record of over 1.4 million tickets had been sold, a figure that eclipsed the previous three Winter Games combined.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the OCO'88's final report, the Committee admits the culmination of fraud charges, a large portion of premier tickets requested by Olympic insiders, and poor communications led to a negative public reaction to the ticketing process.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of the Olympics, both summer and winter, the Organizing Committee worked with a refund policy for returned or unused tickets.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When an event was postponed by at least 24 hours, the ticketholder was eligible for a refund.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Due to weather issues, the 8 events that were scheduled for the first 24 hours had to be rescheduled, resulting in 130,000 ticket refunds totalling CA$2.9 million, with transactions handled by the Royal Bank of Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The city of Calgary is world-renowned for the enthusiasm of its population for volunteer work which is reflected in the annual Calgary Stampede, which also relied heavily on volunteers to run the Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Over 22,000 people signed up for more than 9,400 positions, no matter how inglorious: doctors, lawyers and executives even offered to collect the waste generated during the opening ceremony.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, for the first time, a "Homestay" program was created and several local families opened their homes to visitors from around the world, and others were renting their rooms or houses to those who could not stay in pay a reserve in a hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Klein was among those who felt it necessary that the event be community driven, a decision which allowed the city's welcoming spirit to manifest.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games' mascots, Hidy and Howdy, were designed to evoke images of "western hospitality".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The smiling, cowboy-themed polar bears were popular across Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Played by a team of 150 students from Bishop Carroll High School, the sister-brother pair made up to 300 appearances per month in the lead-up to the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From their introduction at the closing ceremonies of the Sarajevo Games in 1984 until their retirement at the conclusion of the Calgary Games, the pair made about 50,000 appearances.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The iconic mascots graced signs welcoming travellers to Calgary for nearly two decades until they were replaced in 2007.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The mascot's names "Hidy" and "Howdy" were chosen by a public contest.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games were the most expensive Games, summer or winter, to be held at that time, with total expenses exceeding CA$879.6 million.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The high cost was anticipated, as organizers were aware at the outset of their bid that most facilities would have to be constructed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The venues, constructed primarily with public money, were designed to have lasting use beyond the Games and were planned to become the home of several of Canada's national winter sports teams.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The record-breaking cost of the Calgary Olympics came in stark contrast to the original projections during the 1981 bid, which estimated a total cost of CA$218 million, split between CA$126 million in capital costs and CA$92 million in operating costs.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The significant growth in capital expenditures came despite the three levels of government taking over projects which constituted nearly half of the original budgeted capital projects.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Of the total expenses for the Games (CA$879.6 million), the Government of Canada contributed CA$200 million (22.7 per cent), the Government of Alberta contributed CA$130 million (14.8 per cent), and the City of Calgary contributed CA$43 million (4.9 per cent).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CA$320.8 million of government capital contributions not directly included in OCO'88's revenue statements included the Government of Canada constructing the CA$72.2 million Canada Olympic Park, and CA$40 million for the Olympic Oval.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Provincial expenses included CA$14.4 million to build the Canmore Nordic Centre, and CA$25.3 million to build Nakiska.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All three governments contributed to the CA$97.7 million Olympic Saddledome.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were a major economic boom for the city, which had fallen into its worst recession in 40 years following the collapse of both oil and grain prices three years before the games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A report prepared for the city in January 1985 estimated the games would create 11,100 man-years of employment and generate CA$450 million in salaries and wages.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In its post-Games report, OCO'88 estimated the Olympics created CA$1.4 billion in economic benefits across Canada during the 1980s, 70 percent within Alberta, as a result of capital spending, increased tourism and new sporting opportunities created by the facilities.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Olympic torch relay began on November 15, 1987, when the torch was lit at Olympia and Greek runner Stelios Bisbas began what was called "the longest torch run in history".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's, Newfoundland on the Atlantic Ocean two days later and over 88 days, travelled west across the then 10 Canadian provinces and two territories.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It passed through most major cities, north to the Arctic Ocean at Inuvik, Northwest Territories, then west to the Pacific Ocean at Victoria, British Columbia before returning east to Alberta, and finally Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch covered a distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi), the greatest distance for a torch relay in Olympic history until the 2000 Sydney Games, and a sharp contrast to the 1976 Montreal Games when the relay covered only 775 kilometres (482 mi).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The identity of the final torchbearer who would light the Olympic cauldron was one of the Organizing Committee's most closely guarded secrets.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's with Barbara Ann Scott and Ferd Hayward representing Canada's past Olympians and ended with Ken Read and Cathy Priestner carrying the torch into McMahon Stadium representing the nation's current Olympians.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The design of the Olympic Torch for the Calgary games was a reproduction of the main landmark building of the Calgary skyline, the Calgary Tower.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The National Research Council Canada developed the design for the Torch, the base of the torch is made of maple wood, the national tree of Canada, aluminum, and hardened steel, all 100% collected in Canadian territory.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch was designed to remain lit despite the extreme conditions of Canadian winters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Torch had to be light enough for relay runners to carry comfortably, and the final design came in at 60 centimetres in length and 1.7 kilograms in weight.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The maple handle portion included laser-incised pictograms of the 10 official Olympic Winter sports, and lettering was engraved on the steel caldron portion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch used a mixed type of three fuels (gasoline, kerosene and alcohol) to allow a continuous burn during the unpredictable Canadian winter.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 100 torches were manufactured for the Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Governor General Jeanne Sauvé opened the Games on behalf of Queen Elizabeth II as an estimated 1.5 billion people watched the ceremony.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather was a dominant story throughout much of the Games, as strong chinook winds that brought daily temperatures as high as 17 °C (63 °F) wreaked havoc on the schedules for outdoor events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Events were delayed when winds were deemed unsafe for competitors and organizers used artificial snow making equipment to ensure skiing venues were properly prepared.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first time in Olympic history that alpine events were held on artificial snow.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were also marred by the death of the Austrian ski team's doctor, Joerg Oberhammer, on February 25 after a collision with another skier threw him underneath a working snow grooming machine at Nakiska, crushing and killing him instantly.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The top individual competitors at the Olympics were Finnish ski jumper Matti Nykänen and Dutch speed skater Yvonne van Gennip as they each won three gold medals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Italy's Alberto Tomba won gold in two skiing events, his first of five career Olympic medals en route to becoming the first alpine skier to win medals at three Winter Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] East Germany's Katarina Witt defended her 1984 gold medal in women's figure skating, capturing a second gold in Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Her compatriot Christa Rothenburger won the gold medal in the 1000 metre race in speed skating, then went on to win a silver medal in the team sprint cycling event at the 1988 Summer Games to become the only person in Olympic history to win medals at both Olympic Games in the same year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won gold in ice hockey as Nordic neighbours Finland and Sweden took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As it had in 1976, Canada again failed to win an official gold medal as the host of an Olympic Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canadians won two gold medals in demonstration events, including by Sylvie Daigle as one of her five medals in short-track speed skating.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canada's top official performances came in figure skating where Brian Orser and Elizabeth Manley each won silver medals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Boitano won the gold medal over Orser by one-tenth of a point.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Witt won the gold while Thomas won the bronze medal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Manley was not viewed as a medal contender, but skated the greatest performance of her career to come within a fraction of Witt's gold medal-winning score.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] American speed skater Dan Jansen's personal tragedy was one of the more poignant events of the Games as he skated the 500 metre race mere hours after his sister Jane died of leukemia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A gold medal favourite, Jansen chose to compete as he felt it is what his sister would have wanted.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Viewers around the world witnessed his heartbreak as he fell and crashed into the outer wall in the first quarter of his heat.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the 1000 metre race four days later, Jansen was on a world record pace when he again fell.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After failing again in Albertville, Jansen finally won a gold medal at the 1994 Lillehamer Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One of the most popular athletes from the games was British ski jumper Michael Edwards, who gained infamy by placing last in both the 70 and 90 metre events finishing 70 and 53 points behind his next closest competitor, respectively.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Edwards' "heroic failure" made him an instant celebrity; he went from earning £6,000 per year as a plasterer before the Games to making £10,000 per hour per appearance afterward.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Left embarrassed by the spectacle he created, the IOC altered the rules following Calgary to eliminate each nation's right to send at least one athlete and set minimum competition standards for future events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Regardless, the President of the Organizing Committee, Frank King, playfully saluted Edwards' unorthodox sporting legacy, which would also be commemorated with a 2016 feature film, *Eddie the Eagle*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Jamaican bobsleigh team, making their nation's Winter Olympic debut, was also popular in Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The team was the brainchild of a pair of Americans who recruited individuals with strong sprinting ability from the Jamaican military to form the team.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dudley Stokes and Michael White finished the two-man event in 30th place out of 41 competitors and launched the Jamaican team into worldwide fame.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The pair, along with Devon Harris and Chris Stokes, crashed in the four-man event, but were met with cheers from the crowd as they pushed their sled across the finish line.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Their odyssey was made into the 1993 movie *Cool Runnings*, a largely fictionalized comedy by Walt Disney Pictures.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All of the long track world (WR) and Olympic records (OR) that occurred during these Games were later broken at succeeding Winter Olympics and other world events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Prior to 1988, the Winter Olympics were viewed as a second-rate event, in comparison to the Summer Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The IOC had, at one point, considered eliminating it altogether.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] First, there are only a few mountainous areas in the world that would be able to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Second, there were major challenges in generating revenues for the host city and the IOC from such Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, CODA convinced the IOC that it could not only generate enough revenues to make a profit but have enough money left over to ensure a lasting legacy of winter sports development.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] OCO'88 followed mainly the example of LAOOC which organized the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Under LAOOC's president, Peter Ueberroth, he was able to attract a large United States television contract and Los Angeles became the first Olympic host city to make a profit.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 1988 Winter Olympics, OCO'88 attracted financial support from over two dozen major Canadian and multinational corporations, in order to generate millions of dollars in revenues.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For OCO'88, it foresaw some winter sports, like the debut of the Super-G and other new winter sports events, as a way to increase the audience's appeal of the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Thus, for the sponsors, the Games' length of time to 15 days provided an extra weekend of Olympic media coverage to the world.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This additional programming time was filled mainly by TV-friendly demonstration events that are popular in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The 1988 Winter Olympics' exposure to curling, freestyle skiing, and short track speed skating events in Calgary influenced the worldwide popularity of all of them.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] So much so that all these events became the new and official Olympic finals in the period between the 1992 Winter Olympics to the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Hosting the Winter Olympics helped fuel a significant increase in Calgary's reputation on the world stage.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Crosbie Cotton, a reporter for the *Calgary Herald* who covered the city's Olympic odyssey from its 1979 initiative to the closing ceremonies, noted an increased positive outlook of the city's population over time.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] He believed that the populace began to outgrow its "giant inferiority complex" that is "typically Canadian", by replacing it with a new level of confidence as the Games approached.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This outcome helped the city grow from a regional oil and gas centre, best known for the Calgary Stampede, to a destination for international political, economic, and sporting events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] A study prepared for the organizing committee of the 2010 Winter Olympics, (VANOC), claimed that Calgary hosted over 200 national and international sporting competitions between 1987 and 2007, due to the facilities it had constructed for these Olympic Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The Games' enduring popularity within Calgary has been attributed to efforts in making them "everybody's Games." Aside from the sense of community fostered by the high level of volunteer support, OCO'88 included the general public in other ways.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For example, the citizens were given an opportunity to purchase a brick with their names engraved on it.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Those bricks were used to build the Olympic Plaza, where the medal ceremonies were held in 1988.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It remains a popular public park and event site in the city's downtown core today.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After the success of these Olympic Games, Calgary was wanting to bring back the Olympic experience again.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It offered, to the IOC, in becoming a possible alternate host city of the 2002 Winter Olympics, after a bidding scandal resulted in speculation that Salt Lake City would not be able to remain the host city.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Next, the city was attempting to be Canada's bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics, but the COC decided to give it to Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Later, a 2013 *Calgary Sun* online poll found that 81% of respondents said they would support the idea of hosting another Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 13, 2018, Calgary held a public non-binding plebiscite on whether it should bid to host the 2026 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 19, 2018, the results of the plebiscite showed that 56.4% (171,750) of eligible voters said "No", while 43.6% (132,832) of them said "Yes." Therefore, the city council concluded that the bid would be withdrawn.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] In light of the 1976 Summer Olympics' disastrous financial legacy, the Calgary Olympic organizing committee, OCO'88, parlayed its ability to generate television and sponsorship revenues, along with the three levels of government support, into what was ultimately a C$170 million surplus.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] While OCO'88 reported officially a surplus after the Games were over, the accounting practices of the final report did not include federal, provincial, and municipal capital and operations funding infrastructures.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The overall surplus was turned into endowment funds that were split between Canada Olympic Park (C$110 million) and CODA.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] They were subsequently reformed later, in order to manage the Olympic facilities with a trust fund that had grown steadily to be worth over C$200 million by 2013.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Consequently, all five primary facilities built for the 1988 Winter Olympics remained operational for their intended purposes, 25 years after the Games concluded.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Calgary and Canmore became the heart of winter sports in Canada, as CODA (now known as WinSport) established itself as the nation's leader in developing elite winter athletes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 2006 Winter Olympics, a quarter of Canada's Olympic winter athletes were from the Calgary region and three-quarters of its medalists were from or trained in Alberta.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Before 1988, Canada was not a winter sports power.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The nation's five overall medals won in Calgary was its second-best total at a Winter Olympics, behind the seven overall medals it won at the 1932 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid, New York.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After 1988, Canada won an increasing number of gold and overall medals at each successive Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It culminated in an overall performance of 26 medals won at the 2010 Winter Olympics, which included the previous Olympic record of 14 gold medals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Until 2010, Norway won the most Olympic gold medals on home soil at the 1952 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, Norway recaptured the record of winning the most Olympic gold medals at a single Winter Olympics in 2022, claiming 16.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/1988-winter-olympics-p02] At the 2018 Winter Olympics, Canada earned its highest overall medal count in the Winter Olympics to date, with a total of 29 medals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The most common elements of the "afternoon tea" as a meal are the drink itself and baked goods such as cakes, scones and bread and jam, and perhaps sandwiches; these are the pillars of the "traditional afternoon tea" offered by expensive London hotels.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Other types of both drink and food may be offered at home.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] While the custom of drinking tea in the afternoon may have existed from the late 17th century, tea as a meal is a later invention, dating to the late 18th or early 19th centuries.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] An early French reference to "afternoon tea" was made by Madame de Sévigné (1626–1696), who used the term *thé de cinq heures* ("five o’clock tea") in her letters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Ukers notes that Alexander Carlyle used the term "afternoon tea" in his autobiography.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] He describes the ladies of Harrogate serving "afternoon tea or coffee" in 1763.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The *Oxford English Dictionary* provides other early examples of reference to tea as a social gathering.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The earliest is from Jonathan Swift's satirical etiquette guide, *A Complete Collection of Genteel and Ingenious Conversation* (1738), "Whether they meet..at Meals, Tea, or Visits".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] John Wesley and Harriet Martineau also are quoted.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The timing of the tea meal has moved over the centuries in response to the migration of the main meal, dinner.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Until the late 18th century dinner was eaten at what is now called "lunchtime", or in the early afternoon; supper was a later and lighter meal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Dinner remains a midday meal in some regions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Gradually, dinner began to migrate, amid much controversy, until by about 1900 it arrived at its present timing, in most places, in the evening.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] At first, the "tea" meal was often in the early evening, some three or four hours after mid-day dinner; another version of the tea meal was even later, after a supper and before bed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Philosopher Thomas Carlyle and his wife Jane Welsh Carlyle invited guests for 7 pm to their teas in the 1850s, although "afternoon tea" before dinner was also becoming established by this time.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Anna Russell, the Duchess of Bedford, is commonly cited as the originator of the meal of afternoon tea.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Accordingly to the story, at some time in the 1830s or 1840s, the duchess requested a collation of tea and snacks be sent up to her room between the mid-day and evening meals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] During this period, it was the custom for the aristocracy to take their evening meal no earlier than 19:30, or 20:00.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The duchess, who found herself hungry during the intervening period, is said to have devised afternoon tea as a means to endure the long wait until the evening meal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Later, she turned this personal habit into an opportunity for social gathering.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The duchess's role in establishing the custom of afternoon tea is a matter of controversy.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] According to Julia Skinner, there are two theories of her involvement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] One claims that afternoon tea as a meal predates the duchess's birth, and that the timings of meals in Britain had already entered a period of transition.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The other argues that the duchess codified what had been an informal custom, establishing a defined etiquette, menu, and ritual for afternoon tea.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The duchess served as Lady of the Bedchamber to Queen Victoria, a powerful position that allowed her to become a trendsetter.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The custom of afternoon tea first spread among the aristocracy.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] It was later adopted by others in emulation, and by the 1860s–1870s, it had spread to the middle class.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] While afternoon tea (also known as "low tea") became popular among the upper and middle classes, the working class adopted a different meal called "high tea", which was taken around the same time, but much heartier.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] This separate custom emerged due to a change in working habits.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] By the end the 19th century, the concept of tea as a meal, whether in the form of afternoon or high tea, had become established among all social classes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] English author Saki satirised the inanity of these exchanges in his short story, *Tea*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Guests were not expected to stay long – half an hour of pleasant conversation was sufficient.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] If a guest wished to speak with the hostess or with the special guest in whose honour the tea was held, they would approach at an appropriate moment, but should not detain them for long, especially when there were many visitors in the house.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] During the height of the summer tea season, ladies would remain in one place for no more than fifteen minutes before proceeding to the next afternoon tea.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Tea gowns were loose-fitting garments, often made of chiffon, that were traditionally worn by ladies during afternoon teas held at home from 1875 to the 1920s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] They served to provide participants a brief reprieve from the uncomfortable corsets regularly worn in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Commercial establishments known as teahouses or tearooms which served tea as a meal were once common in the UK, but they have declined in popularity since the Second World War.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The first tea room was established at Glasgow in Scotland by tea merchant Stuart Cranston during the 1880s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] His sister, Catherine Cranston, later opened a chain of tea rooms, which included the Willow Tearooms, designed by Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In London, the Aerated Bread Company and Lyons operated popular chains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] A list of significant tea houses in Britain gives more examples.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Unlike the earlier English coffeehouses, these new establishments welcomed female patrons.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Outdoor tea gardens also became popular, and were operated at Hyde Park and Kensington Gardens.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] As in the early 20th century, hotels and restaurants have embraced the trend, and the service often extends beyond dining rooms into lounge areas and common spaces.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Guests are willing to pay substantial sums for a modest meal that is easy to prepare in the kitchen and generates income during the lull between lunch and dinner.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Tea establishments and restaurants usually offer patrons a choice of at least a dozen tea varieties, including traditional black teas, herbal infusions, rooibos, and green teas.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Food and beverage managers in British hotels design menus emphasising variety – in dishes as well as tea types.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Some establishments even employ tea sommeliers who create a tea menu including varieties from around the world.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Britain, afternoon tea occupies a dual position: on one hand, it is sometimes considered an outdated tradition; on the other hand, it remains an important part of the country's gastronomic identity.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Today, the tradition is maintained at the Ritz Hotel, London, and other hotels.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In London, the major hotels compete for the annual Afternoon Tea Awards.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Canada, afternoon tea ceremonies at the grand railway hotels are a well-known tradition across the country.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Australia, venues nationwide ranging from the Hotel Windsor in Melbourne, which first served high tea in 1883, to hotels opened in the 21st century serve a variety of afternoon teas, including traditional, modern, and novel, sometimes with items flavoured using local ingredients.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In the United States, the "afternoon tea industry" is also primarily the province of destination hotels.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] A multi-tiered stand for serving sandwiches, scones, and other baked goods is often placed in the centre of the table, along with napkins.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The bottom tier holds sandwiches, the middle tier scones, and the top tier petit fours and sweet cakes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Typically, black tea is served, often Darjeeling, Assam, Earl Grey, or Ceylon tea, served with milk, or lemon if serving Chinese or Russian-style tea.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] A stereotypical expression "You'll have had your tea", meaning "I imagine you have already eaten", is used to parody people from Edinburgh as being rather stingy with hospitality.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] A BBC Radio 4 comedy series of this name was made by Graeme Garden and Barry Cryer.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Outside Britain, the term "high tea" is sometimes used as synonym for "afternoon tea".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Afternoon tea has become a symbol of English culture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Its presence (or absence) in the former colonies of the British Empire reflects the rise and decline of English influence, as well as which traditions were valued and preserved.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Britain imported goods and raw materials from its colonies, and exported its cultural traditions to them.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] By the end of the 19th century, colonial officials (such as governors) had firmly adopted afternoon tea into their routines and continued the tradition at new posts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Thus, afternoon tea became part of the colonial legacy, rooted in many post-colonial cultures, and continues to exist in both modified and unchanged forms.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Afternoon tea became widespread in countries of the former British Empire, including Australia, Hong Kong, India, Canada, Kenya, Malta, and South Africa.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The custom is also observed in society and luxury hotels in countries such as Austria, Belgium, Hungary, Greece, Denmark, Italy, Norway, Poland, Finland, Czech Republic, Sweden, and Switzerland.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Russia, the term "five o'clock tea" became a symbol of refined lifestyle and entered the vocabulary of the Russian intelligentsia in the late 19th century; among lower social strata, afternoon tea with a samovar also became a habit.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In South Africa, New Zealand, and Australia, a small informal social gathering usually at someone's home for tea and a light meal (e.g. biscuits, scones, or slices of cake or sandwiches) in the mid-afternoon is referred to as "afternoon tea".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] More generally, any light meal or snack taken at mid-afternoon, with or without tea or another hot drink, may also be referred to as "afternoon tea".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] When taken at mid-morning instead of mid-afternoon, the term "morning tea" is used in place of "afternoon tea" in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] These usages have declined in popularity in recent years, in tandem with the rise in coffee culture, particularly in Australia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] The term *high tea* is now used in the southern hemisphere to describe formal afternoon teas.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] Formal afternoon teas are often held outside the private home in commercial tea rooms, function venues, hotels, or similar.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Australia and New Zealand, a break from work or school taken at mid-morning is frequently known as "morning tea", and a break at mid-afternoon as "afternoon tea," both with or without the tea being drunk.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] A *smoko*, originally meaning a cigarette break, is also used as slang for a break, especially for people working in manual work.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/afternoon-tea] In Australia and New Zealand, tea also refers to "dinner".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] An **arcade** is a succession of contiguous arches, with each arch supported by a colonnade of columns or piers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Exterior arcades are designed to provide a sheltered walkway for pedestrians; they include many loggias, but here arches are not an essential element.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] An arcade may feature arches on both sides of the walkway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Alternatively, a blind arcade superimposes arcading against a solid wall.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Blind arcades are a feature of Romanesque architecture that influenced Gothic architecture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] In the Gothic architectural tradition, the arcade can be located in the interior, in the lowest part of the wall of the nave, supporting the triforium and the clerestory in a cathedral, or on the exterior, in which they are usually part of the walkways that surround the courtyard and cloisters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] A different, related meaning is "a covered passage with shops on one or both sides".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Many medieval open arcades housed shops or stalls, either in the arcaded space itself, or set into the main wall behind.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] From this, "arcade" has become a general word for a group of shops in a single building, regardless of the architectural form.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The word "arcade" comes from French *arcade* from Provençal *arcada* or Italian *arcata*, based on Latin *arcus*, ‘bow’ (see arc and arch).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] A related but ambiguous term is **arcature**, which is either a small arcade or a blind arcade.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Arcades go back to at least the Ancient Greek architecture of the Hellenistic period, and were much used by the Romans, for example at the base of the Colosseum.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Church cloisters very often use arcading.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Islamic architecture very often uses arcades in and outside mosques in particular.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] In Renaissance architecture elegant arcading was often used as a prominent feature of facades, for example in the Ospedale degli Innocenti (commissioned 1419) or the courtyard of the Palazzo Bardi, both by Filippo Brunelleschi in Florence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The French architect, Bertrand Lemoine, described the period, 1786 to 1935, as *l’Ère des passages couverts* (the Arcade Era).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] He was referring to the grand shopping "arcades" that flourished across Europe during that period.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] A shopping arcade refers to a multiple-vendor space, operating under a covered roof.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Typically, the roof was constructed of glass to allow for natural light and to reduce the need for candles or electric lighting.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The 18th and 19th century arcades were designed to attract the genteel middle classes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] In time, these arcades came to be the place to shop and to be seen.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Arcades offered shoppers the promise of an enclosed space away from the chaos that characterised the noisy, dirty streets; a warm, dry space away from the harsh elements, and a safe haven where people could socialise and spend their leisure time.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] As thousands of glass covered arcades spread across Europe, they became grander and more ornately decorated.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] By the mid-nineteenth century, they had become prominent centres of fashion and social life.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Promenading in these arcades became a popular nineteenth-century pastime for the emerging middle classes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] During the 16th-century, a pattern of market trading using mobile stalls under covered arcades was established in Florence, from where it spread throughout Italy.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Examples of the earliest open loggias include: Mercato Nuovo (1547) by Giovanni Battista del Tasso (and funded by the Medici family); Mercato Vecchio, Florence by Giorgio Vasari (1567) and Loggia del Grano (1619) by Giulio Parigi.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Arcades soon spread across Europe, North America and the antipodes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Examples of these grand shopping arcades include: Palais Royal in Paris (opened in 1784); Passage de Feydeau in Paris (opened in 1791); London's Piccadilly Arcade (1810) and Milan's Galleria Vittorio Emanuele (1878).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Some examples of arcades in North America include New York's Paddock Arcade (1850), Ohio's Dayton Arcade (1904), and Rhode Island's Westminster Arcade (1828).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Other notable nineteenth century grand arcades include the Galeries Royales Saint-Hubert in Brussels which was inaugurated in 1847 and Istanbul's Çiçek Pasajı opened in 1870.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Shopping arcades were the precursor to the modern shopping mall, and the word "arcade" is now often used for malls which do not use the architectural form at all.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The Palais-Royal, which opened in 1784 and became one of the most important marketplaces in Paris, is generally regarded as the earliest example of the grand shopping arcades.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Originally, a royal palace, the complex consisted of gardens, shops and entertainment venues situated under the original colonnades.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The area boasted some 145 boutiques, cafés, salons, hair salons, bookshops, museums, and numerous refreshment kiosks as well as two theatres.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The retail outlets specialised in luxury goods such as fine jewellery, furs, paintings and furniture designed to appeal to the wealthy elite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Retailers operating out of the Palais complex were among the first in Europe to abandon the system of bartering, and adopt fixed-prices thereby sparing their clientele the hassle of bartering.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Stores were fitted with long glass exterior windows which allowed the emerging middle-classes to window shop and indulge in fantasies, even when they may not have been able to afford the high retail prices.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Thus, the Palais-Royal became one of the first examples of a new style of shopping arcade, frequented by both the aristocracy and the middle classes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] It developed a reputation as being a site of sophisticated conversation, revolving around the salons, cafés, and bookshops, but also became a place frequented by off-duty soldiers and was a favourite haunt of prostitutes, many of whom rented apartments in the building.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] One of the earliest British examples of a shopping arcade, the Covered Market, Oxford, England was officially opened on 1 November 1774 and is still active today.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] The Covered Market was started in response to a general wish to clear "untidy, messy and unsavoury stalls" from the main streets of central Oxford.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] John Gwynn, the architect of Magdalen Bridge, drew up the plans and designed the High Street front with its four entrances.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] In 1772, the newly formed Market committee, half of whose members came from the town and half from the university, accepted an estimate of nine hundred and sixteen pounds ten shillings, for the building of twenty butchers' shops.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Twenty more soon followed, and after 1773 meat was allowed to be sold only inside the market.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] From this nucleus the market grew, with stalls for garden produce, pig meat, dairy products and fish.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Gostiny Dvor in St Petersburg, Russia is another early shopping arcade and remains the largest shopping center in the city.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Gostiny Dvor translates into *Merchants' Arcade*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Building commenced in 1757 to an elaborate design by Bartolomeo Rastrelli, but that subsequently was discarded in favour of a less expensive and more functional Neoclassical design submitted by Jean-Baptiste Vallin de la Mothe (1729–1800).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Throughout the following century, Gostiny Dvor was augmented, resulting in ten indoor streets and as many as 178 shops by the 20th century.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] During the post-World War II reconstructions, its inner walls were demolished and a huge shopping mall came into being.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] This massive 18th-century structure got a face-lift recently and entered the 21st century as one of the most fashionable shopping centres in Eastern Europe.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] An early French arcade is the Passage du Caire created in 1798 as a tribute to the French campaign in Egypt and Syria.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] It was appreciated by the public for its protection from the weather, noise and filth of the streets.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] A year later American architect William Thayer created the Passage des Panoramas with a row of shops passing between two panorama paintings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Shopping arcades increasingly were built in the second Bourbon Restoration.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arcade-architecture] Upper levels of arcades often contained apartments and sometimes brothels.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The **Arts and Crafts movement** was an international trend in the decorative and fine arts that developed earliest and most fully in the British Isles and subsequently spread across the British Empire and to the rest of Europe and North America.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Broadly, the beginning of the movement can be dated to the 1880s, with the term itself first used in 1887, and by about 1920 it can be considered as over in the UK, although the term continued in spurious use for various popular elements in design.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Initiated in reaction against the perceived impoverishment of the decorative arts and the conditions in which they were produced, the movement flourished in Europe and North America between about 1880 and 1920.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some consider that it is the root of the Modern Style, a British expression of what later came to be called the Art Nouveau movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Others regard it as the incarnation of Art Nouveau in England.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Others consider Art and Crafts to be in opposition to Art Nouveau.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts indeed criticised Art Nouveau for its use of industrial materials such as iron.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Japan, it emerged in the 1920s as the Mingei movement, promoting traditional craftsmanship.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Cobden-Sanderson at a meeting of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society in 1887, although the principles and style on which it was based had been developing in England for at least 20 years.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was inspired by the ideas of historian Thomas Carlyle, art critic John Ruskin, and designer William Morris.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Scotland, it is associated with key figures such as Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Viollet-le-Duc's books on nature and Gothic art also play an essential part in the aesthetics of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts movement emerged from the attempt to reform design and decoration in mid-19th-century Britain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was a reaction against a perceived decline in standards that the reformers associated with machinery and factory production.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Their critique was sharpened by the items that they saw in Great Exhibition of 1851, which they considered to be excessively ornate, artificial, and ignorant of the qualities of the materials used.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Art historian Nikolaus Pevsner writes that the exhibits showed "ignorance of that basic need in creating patterns, the integrity of the surface", as well as displaying "vulgarity in detail".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Design reform began with Exhibition organisers Henry Cole (1808–1882), Owen Jones (1809–1874), Matthew Digby Wyatt (1820–1877), and Richard Redgrave (1804–1888), all of whom deprecated excessive ornament and impractical or badly-made things.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The *Grammar of Ornament* was particularly influential, liberally distributed as a student prize and running into nine reprints by 1910.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Jones declared that ornament "must be secondary to the thing decorated", that there must be "fitness in the ornament to the thing ornamented", and that wallpapers and carpets must not have any patterns "suggestive of anything but a level or plain".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A fabric or wallpaper in the Great Exhibition might be decorated with a natural motif made to look as real as possible, whereas these writers advocated flat and simplified natural motifs.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Redgrave insisted that "style" demanded sound construction before ornamentation, and a proper awareness of the quality of materials used.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] However, the design reformers of the mid-19th century did not go as far as the designers of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] They were more concerned with ornamentation than construction, they had an incomplete understanding of methods of manufacture, and they did not criticise industrial methods as such.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By contrast, the Arts and Crafts movement was as much a movement of social reform as design reform, and its leading practitioners did not separate the two.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some of the ideas of the movement were anticipated by Augustus Pugin (1812–1852), a leader in the Gothic Revival in architecture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] For example, he advocated truth to material, structure, and function, as did the Arts and Crafts artists.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Pugin articulated the tendency of social critics to compare the faults of modern society with the Middle Ages, such as the sprawling growth of cities and the treatment of the poor – a tendency that became routine with Ruskin, Morris, and the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts philosophy was derived in large measure from John Ruskin's social criticism, deeply influenced by the work of Thomas Carlyle.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin related the moral and social health of a nation to the qualities of its architecture and to the nature of its work.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin considered the sort of mechanised production and division of labour that had been created in the Industrial Revolution to be "servile labour", and he thought that a healthy and moral society required independent workers who designed the things that they made.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He believed factory-made works to be "dishonest," and that handwork and craftsmanship merged dignity with labour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] On the artistic side Ruskin was influenced by his contemporary Viollet-le-Duc whom he taught to all of his pupils.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In a letter to one of his pupils Ruskin writes: "There is only one book of architecture of any value and that contains every thing, rightly, Monsieur Viollet-le-Duc's Dictionary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] According to some, Ruskin's influence on Arts and Crafts was supplanted in 1860 by that of Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His followers favoured craft production over industrial manufacture and were concerned about the loss of traditional skills, but they were more troubled by the effects of the factory system than by machinery itself.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris's idea of "handicraft" was essentially work without any division of labour rather than work without any sort of machinery.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris admired Ruskin's *The Seven Lamps of Architecture* and *The Stones of Venice* and had read *Modern Painters*, but he did not share Ruskin's admiration for J.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Turner and his writings on art indicate a lack of interest in easel painting as such.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] On his side, Ruskin dissented firmly from the idea that became Arts-and-Crafts orthodoxy, that decoration should be flat and should not represent three-dimensional forms.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris (1834–1896) was the towering figure in late 19th-century design and the main influence on the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The aesthetic and social vision of the movement grew out of ideas that he developed in the 1850s with the Birmingham Set – a group of students at the University of Oxford including Edward Burne-Jones, who combined a love of Romantic literature with a commitment to social reform.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] John William Mackail notes that, for the Set, "Carlyle's *Past and Present* stood alongside of [Ruskin's] *Modern Painters* as inspired and absolute truth." The medievalism of Malory's *Morte d'Arthur* set the standard for their early style.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Burne-Jones' words, they intended to "wage Holy warfare against the age".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris began experimenting with various crafts and designing furniture and interiors.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He was personally involved in manufacture as well as design, which was the hallmark of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin had argued that the separation of the intellectual act of design from the manual act of physical creation was both socially and aesthetically damaging.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris further developed this idea, insisting that no work should be carried out in his workshops before he had personally mastered the appropriate techniques and materials, arguing that "without dignified, creative human occupation people became disconnected from life".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1861, Morris began making furniture and decorative objects commercially, modelling his designs on medieval styles and using bold forms and strong colours.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His patterns were based on flora and fauna, and his products were inspired by the vernacular or domestic traditions of the British countryside.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some were deliberately left unfinished in order to display the beauty of the materials and the work of the craftsman, thus creating a rustic appearance.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris strove to unite all the arts within the decoration of the home, emphasising nature and simplicity of form.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris shared Ruskin's critique of industrial society and at one time or another attacked the modern factory, the use of machinery, the division of labour, capitalism and the loss of traditional craft methods.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But his attitude to machinery was inconsistent.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He said at one point that production by machinery was "altogether an evil", but at others times, he was willing to commission work from manufacturers who were able to meet his standards with the aid of machines.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris said that in a "true society", where neither luxuries nor cheap trash were made, machinery could be improved and used to reduce the hours of labour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris insisted that the artist should be a craftsman-designer working by hand and advocated a society of free craftspeople, such as he believed had existed during the Middle Ages.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] "Because craftsmen took pleasure in their work", he wrote, "the Middle Ages was a period of greatness in the art of the common people. ...
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's followers also had differing views about machinery and the factory system.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, a central figure in the Arts and Crafts movement, said in 1888, that, "We do not reject the machine, we welcome it.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris and his followers believed the division of labour on which modern industry depended was undesirable, but the extent to which every design should be carried out by the designer was a matter for debate and disagreement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Not all Arts and Crafts artists carried out every stage in the making of goods themselves, and it was only in the 20th century that that became essential to the definition of craftsmanship.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Although Morris was famous for getting hands-on experience himself of many crafts (including weaving, dyeing, printing, calligraphy and embroidery), he did not regard the separation of designer and executant in his factory as problematic.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Walter Crane, a close political associate of Morris's, took an unsympathetic view of the division of labour on both moral and artistic grounds, and strongly advocated that designing and making should come from the same hand.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lewis Foreman Day, a friend and contemporary of Crane's, as unstinting as Crane in his admiration of Morris, disagreed strongly with Crane.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He thought that the separation of design and execution was not only inevitable in the modern world, but also that only that sort of specialisation allowed the best in design and the best in making.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Few of the founders of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society insisted that the designer should also be the maker, although they considered it important that the maker should be credited, which was the practice in the catalogues of their exhibitions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of the Arts and Crafts movement designers were socialists, including Morris, T.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, Philip Webb, Charles Faulkner, and A.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In the early 1880s, Morris was spending more of his time on promoting socialism than on designing and making.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee established a community of craftsmen called the Guild of Handicraft in east London, later moving to Chipping Campden.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Those adherents who were not socialists, such as Alfred Hoare Powell, advocated a more humane and personal relationship between employer and employee.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lewis Foreman Day was another successful and influential Arts and Crafts designer who was not a socialist, despite his long friendship with Crane.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Britain, the movement was associated with dress reform, ruralism, the garden city movement and the folk-song revival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] All were linked, in some degree, by the ideal of "the Simple Life".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In continental Europe the movement was associated with the preservation of national traditions in building, the applied arts, domestic design and costume.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's designs quickly became popular, attracting interest when his company's work was exhibited at the 1862 International Exhibition in London.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Much of this work is directly inspired from the Dictionnaire of Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Most of Morris & Co's early work was for churches and Morris won important interior design commissions at St James's Palace and the South Kensington Museum (now the Victoria and Albert Museum).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Later his work became popular with the middle and upper classes, despite his wish to create a democratic art, and by the end of the 19th century, Arts and Crafts design in houses and domestic interiors was the dominant style in Britain, copied in products made by conventional industrial methods.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The spread of Arts and Crafts ideas during the late 19th and early 20th centuries resulted in the establishment of many associations and craft communities, although Morris had little to do with them because of his preoccupation with socialism at the time.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A hundred and thirty Arts and Crafts organisations were formed in Britain, most between 1895 and 1905.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Mackmurdo formed the Century Guild, a partnership of designers including Selwyn Image, Herbert Horne, Clement Heaton and Benjamin Creswick.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1884, the Art Workers Guild was initiated by five young architects, William Lethaby, Edward Prior, Ernest Newton, Mervyn Macartney and Gerald C.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Horsley, with the goal of bringing together fine and applied arts and raising the status of the latter.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was directed originally by George Blackall Simonds.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By 1890 the Guild had 150 members, representing the increasing number of practitioners of the Arts and Crafts style.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The London department store Liberty, founded in 1875, was a prominent retailer of goods in the style and of the "artistic dress" favoured by followers of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1887, the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society, which gave its name to the movement, was formed with Walter Crane as president, holding its first exhibition in the New Gallery, London, in November 1888.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was the first show of contemporary decorative arts in London since the Grosvenor Gallery's Winter Exhibition of 1881.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris & Co. was well represented in the exhibition with furniture, fabrics, carpets and embroideries.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Edward Burne-Jones observed, "here for the first time one can measure a bit the change that has happened in the last twenty years".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The society still exists as the Society of Designer Craftsmen.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, a major late practitioner of the style in England, founded the Guild and School of Handicraft in the East End of London.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild was a craft co-operative modelled on the medieval guilds and intended to give working men satisfaction in their craftsmanship.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Skilled craftsmen, working on the principles of Ruskin and Morris, were to produce hand-crafted goods and manage a school for apprentices.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The idea was greeted with enthusiasm by almost everyone except Morris, who was by now involved with promoting socialism and thought Ashbee's scheme trivial.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] From 1888 to 1902 the guild prospered, employing about 50 men.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1902 Ashbee relocated the guild out of London to begin an experimental community in Chipping Campden in the Cotswolds.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild's work is characterised by plain surfaces of hammered silver, flowing wirework and coloured stones in simple settings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee designed jewellery and silver tableware.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild flourished at Chipping Camden but did not prosper and was liquidated in 1908.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some craftsmen stayed, contributing to the tradition of modern craftsmanship in the area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Voysey (1857–1941) was an Arts and Crafts architect who also designed fabrics, tiles, ceramics, furniture and metalwork.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His style combined simplicity with sophistication.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His wallpapers and textiles, featuring stylised bird and plant forms in bold outlines with flat colours, were used widely.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's thought influenced the distributism of G.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By 1910, there was a fashion for "Arts and Crafts" and all things hand-made.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society held eleven exhibitions between 1888 and 1916.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By the outbreak of war in 1914 it was in decline and faced a crisis.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Its 1912 exhibition had been a financial failure.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Nikolaus Pevsner in his book *Pioneers of Modern Design* presents the Arts and Crafts movement as design radicals who influenced the modern movement, but failed to change and were eventually superseded by it.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The British artist potter Bernard Leach brought to England many ideas he had developed in Japan with the social critic Yanagi Soetsu about the moral and social value of simple crafts; both were enthusiastic readers of Ruskin.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Leach was an active propagandist for these ideas, which struck a chord with practitioners of the crafts in the inter-war years, and he expounded them in *A Potter's Book*, published in 1940, which denounced industrial society in terms as vehement as those of Ruskin and Morris.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Thus the Arts and Crafts philosophy was perpetuated among British craft workers in the 1950s and 1960s, long after the demise of the Arts and Crafts movement and at the high tide of Modernism.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] British Utility furniture of the 1940s also derived from Arts and Crafts principles.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] One of its main promoters, Gordon Russell, chairman of the Utility Furniture Design Panel, was imbued with Arts and Crafts ideas.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He manufactured furniture in the Cotswold Hills, a region of Arts and Crafts furniture-making since Ashbee, and he was a member of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris's biographer, Fiona MacCarthy, detected the Arts and Crafts philosophy even behind the Festival of Britain (1951), the work of the designer Terence Conran (1931–2020) and the founding of the British Crafts Council in the 1970s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The beginnings of the Arts and Crafts movement in Scotland were in the stained glass revival of the 1850s, pioneered by James Ballantine (1806–1877).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His major works included the great west window of Dunfermline Abbey and the scheme for St Giles Cathedral, Edinburgh.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Glasgow it was pioneered by Daniel Cottier (1838–1891), who had probably studied with Ballantine, and was directly influenced by William Morris, Ford Madox Brown and John Ruskin.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His key works included the *Baptism of Christ* in Paisley Abbey, (c.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His followers included Stephen Adam and his son of the same name.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Glasgow-born designer and theorist Christopher Dresser (1834–1904) was one of the first, and most important, independent designers, a pivotal figure in the Aesthetic Movement and a major contributor to the allied Anglo-Japanese movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement had an "extraordinary flowering" in Scotland where it was represented by the development of the 'Glasgow Style' which was based on the talent of the Glasgow School of Art.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Celtic revival took hold here, and motifs such as the Glasgow rose became popularised.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Charles Rennie Mackintosh (1868–1928) and the Glasgow School of Art were to influence others worldwide.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The situation in Wales was different from elsewhere in the UK.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Insofar as craftsmanship was concerned, Arts and Crafts was a *revivalist* campaign.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But in Wales, at least until the First World War, a genuine craft tradition still existed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Local materials, stone or clay, continued to be used as a matter of course.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Scotland become known in the Arts and Crafts movement for its stained glass; Wales would become known for its pottery.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By the mid 19th century, the heavy, salt glazes used for generations by local craftsmen had gone out of fashion, not least as mass-produced ceramics undercut prices.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But the Arts and Crafts Movement brought new appreciation to their work.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Horace W Elliot, an English gallerist, visited the Ewenny Pottery (which dated back to the 17th century) in 1885, to both find local pieces and encourage a style compatible with the movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The pieces he brought back to London for the next twenty years revivified interest in Welsh pottery work.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A key promoter of the Arts and Crafts movement in Wales was Owen Morgan Edwards.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Edwards was a reforming politician dedicated to renewing Welsh pride by exposing its people to their own language and history.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] For Edwards, "There is nothing that Wales requires more than an education in the arts and crafts." – though Edwards was more inclined to resurrecting Welsh Nationalism than admiring glazes or rustic integrity.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In architecture, Clough Williams-Ellis sought to renew interest in ancient building, reviving "rammed earth" or pisé construction in Britain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement spread to Ireland, representing an important time for the nation's cultural development, a visual counterpart to the literary revival of the same time and was a publication of Irish nationalism.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts use of stained glass was popular in Ireland, with Harry Clarke the best-known artist and also with Evie Hone.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The architecture of the style is represented by the Honan Chapel (1916) in Cork city in the grounds of University College Cork.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Other architects practising in Ireland included Sir Edwin Lutyens (Heywood House in Co.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Laois, Lambay Island and the Irish National War Memorial Gardens in Dublin) and Frederick 'Pa' Hicks (Malahide Castle estate buildings and round tower).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Irish Celtic motifs were popular with the movement in silvercraft, carpet design, book illustrations, and hand-carved furniture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Widely exhibited in Europe, the Arts and Crafts style's simplicity inspired designers like Henry van de Velde and styles such as Art Nouveau, the Dutch De Stijl group, Vienna Secession, and eventually the Bauhaus style.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Pevsner regarded the style as a prelude to Modernism, which used simple forms without ornamentation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The earliest Arts and Crafts activity in continental Europe was in Belgium in about 1890, where the English style inspired artists and architects including Henry Van de Velde, Gabriel Van Dievoet, Gustave Serrurier-Bovy, and a group known as *La Libre Esthétique* (Free Aesthetic).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts products were admired in Austria and Germany in the early 20th century, and under their inspiration design moved rapidly forward while it stagnated in Britain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Wiener Werkstätte, founded in 1903 by Josef Hoffmann and Koloman Moser, was influenced by the Arts and Crafts principles of the "unity of the arts" and the hand-made.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] However, its leading members, van de Velde and Hermann Muthesius, had conflicting opinions about standardisation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Muthesius believed that it was essential were Germany to become a leading nation in trade and culture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Finland, an idealistic artists' colony in Helsinki was designed by Herman Gesellius, Armas Lindgren, and Eliel Saarinen, who worked in the National Romantic style, akin to the British Gothic Revival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Hungary, under the influence of Ruskin and Morris, a group of artists and architects, including Károly Kós, Aladár Körösfői-Kriesch, and Ede Toroczkai Wigand, discovered the folk art and vernacular architecture of Transylvania.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of Kós's buildings, including those in the Budapest zoo and the Wekerle estate in the same city, show this influence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Russia, Viktor Hartmann, Viktor Vasnetsov, Yelena Polenova, and other artists associated with Abramtsevo Colony sought to revive the quality of medieval Russian decorative arts quite independently from the movement in Great Britain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Iceland, Sölvi Helgason's work shows Arts and Crafts influence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In the United States, the Arts and Crafts style initiated a variety of attempts to reinterpret European Arts and Crafts ideals for Americans.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] These included the "Craftsman"-style architecture, furniture, and other decorative arts such as designs promoted by Gustav Stickley in his magazine, *The Craftsman* and designs produced on the Roycroft campus as publicised in Elbert Hubbard's *The Fra*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Both men used their magazines as a vehicle to promote the goods produced with the Craftsman workshop in Eastwood, New York, and Elbert Hubbard's Roycroft campus in East Aurora, New York.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A host of imitators of Stickley's furniture (the designs of which are often mislabelled the "Mission Style") included three companies established by his brothers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The terms *American Craftsman* or ***Craftsman style*** are often used to denote the style of architecture, interior design, and decorative arts that prevailed between the dominant eras of Art Nouveau and Art Deco in the US, or approximately the period from 1910 to 1925.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement was particularly notable for the professional opportunities it opened up for women as artisans, designers and entrepreneurs who founded and ran, or were employed by, such successful enterprises as the Kalo Shops, Pewabic Pottery, Rookwood Pottery, and Tiffany Studios.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Canada, the term *Arts and Crafts* predominates, but *Craftsman* is also recognised.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] While the Europeans tried to recreate the virtuous crafts being replaced by industrialisation, Americans tried to establish a new type of virtue to replace heroic craft production: well-decorated middle-class homes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] They claimed that the simple but refined aesthetics of Arts and Crafts decorative arts would ennoble the new experience of industrial consumerism, making individuals more rational and society more harmonious.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The American Arts and Crafts movement was the aesthetic counterpart of its contemporary political philosophy, progressivism.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Characteristically, when the Arts and Crafts Society began in October 1897 in Chicago, it was at Hull House, one of the first American settlement houses for social reform.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts ideals disseminated in America through journal and newspaper writing were supplemented by societies that sponsored lectures.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first was organised in Boston in the late 1890s, when a group of influential architects, designers, and educators determined to bring to America the design reforms begun in Britain by William Morris; they met to organise an exhibition of contemporary craft objects.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first meeting was held on 4 January 1897, at the Museum of Fine Arts (MFA) in Boston to organise an exhibition of contemporary crafts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] When craftsmen, consumers, and manufacturers realised the aesthetic and technical potential of the applied arts, the process of design reform in Boston started.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Present at this meeting were General Charles Loring, Chairman of the Trustees of the MFA; William Sturgis Bigelow and Denman Ross, collectors, writers and MFA trustees; Ross Turner, painter; Sylvester Baxter, art critic for the *Boston Transcript*; Howard Baker, A.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Longfellow Jr.; and Ralph Clipson Sturgis, architect.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first American Arts and Crafts Exhibition began on 5 April 1897, at Copley Hall, Boston, featuring more than 1000 objects made by 160 craftsmen, half of whom were women.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some of the advocates of the exhibit were Langford Warren, founder of Harvard's School of Architecture; Mrs.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Richard Morris Hunt; Arthur Astor Carey and Edwin Mead, social reformers; and Will H.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Castle in the Clouds (also known as *Lucknow*), a mountaintop estate in the Ossipee Mountains of New Hampshire, built in 1913–14 by the Boston architect J.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Hapgood, and the contemporary studio craft style.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Batchelder in Pasadena, California, and idiosyncratic furniture of Charles Rohlfs all demonstrate the influence of Arts and Crafts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Canada, artist, teacher and architect George Agnew Reid (1860–1947) was a major proponent of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Reid was interested in linking art and social issues, and he felt strongly that visual and applied arts could act as tools for personal and social improvement through public access to beauty and good design.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Reid brought his "art for life's sake" sensibility to his painting practice, specifically with the murals he created in and around Toronto.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Restored and landmark-protected examples are still present in America, especially in California in Berkeley and Pasadena, and the sections of other towns originally developed during the era and not experiencing post-war urban renewal.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Mission Revival, Prairie School, and the 'California bungalow' styles of residential building remain popular in the United States today.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] As theoreticians, educators, and prolific artists in mediums from printmaking to pottery and pastel, two of the most influential figures were Arthur Wesley Dow (1857–1922) on the East Coast and Pedro Joseph de Lemos (1882–1954) in California.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His purpose was to create objects that were finely crafted and beautifully rendered.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Among his unorthodox teachings was his belief that manufactured products could express "the sublime beauty" and that great insight was to be found in the abstract "design forms" of pre-Columbian civilisations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Museum of the American Arts and Crafts Movement (MAACM) in St Petersburg, Florida, displays an extensive collection of fine and decorative arts from the American Arts and Crafts movement (c.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Japan, Yanagi Sōetsu, creator of the Mingei movement which promoted folk art from the 1920s onwards, was influenced by the writings of Morris and Ruskin.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Like the Arts and Crafts movement in Europe, Mingei sought to preserve traditional crafts and often used medieval, romantic, or folk styles of decoration.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It advocated economic and social reform and was anti-industrial in its orientation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It had a strong influence on the arts in Europe until it was displaced by Modernism in the 1930s, and its influence continued among craft makers, designers, and town planners long afterwards.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of the leaders of the Arts and Crafts movement were trained as architects (e.g.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lethaby) and it was on building that the movement had its most visible and lasting influence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Red House, in Bexleyheath, London, designed for Morris in 1859 by architect Philip Webb, exemplifies the early Arts and Crafts style, with its well-proportioned solid forms, wide porches, steep roof, pointed window arches, brick fireplaces and wooden fittings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Webb rejected classical and other revivals of historical styles based on grand buildings, and based his design on British vernacular architecture, expressing the texture of ordinary materials, such as stone and tiles, with an asymmetrical and picturesque building composition.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The London suburb of Bedford Park, built mainly in the 1880s and 1890s, has about 360 Arts and Crafts style houses and was once famous for its Aesthetic residents.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Several Almshouses were built in the Arts and Crafts style, for example, Whiteley Village, Surrey, built between 1914 and 1917, with over 280 buildings, and the Dyers Almshouses, Sussex, built between 1939 and 1971.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Letchworth Garden City, the first garden city, was inspired by Arts and Crafts ideals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first houses were designed by Barry Parker and Raymond Unwin in the vernacular style popularised by the movement and the town became associated with high-mindedness and simple living.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Gertrude Jekyll applied Arts and Crafts principles to garden design.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] She worked with the English architect, Sir Edwin Lutyens, for whose projects she created numerous landscapes, and who designed her home Munstead Wood, near Godalming in Surrey.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Jekyll created the gardens for Bishopsbarns, the home of York architect Walter Brierley, an exponent of the Arts and Crafts movement and known as the "Lutyens of the North".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The garden for Brierley's final project, Goddards in York, was the work of George Dillistone, a gardener who worked with Lutyens and Jekyll at Castle Drogo.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] At Goddards the garden incorporated a number of features that reflected the arts and crafts style of the house, such as the use of hedges and herbaceous borders to divide the garden into a series of outdoor rooms.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Another notable Arts and Crafts garden is Hidcote Manor Garden designed by Lawrence Johnston which is also laid out in a series of outdoor rooms and where, like Goddards, the landscaping becomes less formal further away from the house.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Other examples of Arts and Crafts gardens include Hestercombe Gardens, Lytes Cary Manor and the gardens of some of the architectural examples of arts and crafts buildings (listed above).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Morris's ideas were adopted by the New Education Movement in the late 1880s, which incorporated handicraft teaching in schools at Abbotsholme (1889) and Bedales (1892), and his influence has been noted in the social experiments of Dartington Hall during the mid-20th century.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Arts and Crafts practitioners in Britain were critical of the government system of art education based on design in the abstract with little teaching of practical craft.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] This lack of craft training also caused concern in industrial and official circles, and in 1884 a Royal Commission (accepting the advice of William Morris) recommended that art education should pay more attention to the suitability of design to the material in which it was to be executed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] The first school to make this change was the Birmingham School of Arts and Crafts, which "led the way in introducing executed design to the teaching of art and design nationally (working in the material for which the design was intended rather than designing on paper).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Other local authority schools also began to introduce more practical teaching of crafts, and by the 1890s Arts and Crafts ideals were being disseminated by members of the Art Workers Guild into art schools throughout the country.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Members of the Guild held influential positions: Walter Crane was director of the Manchester School of Art and subsequently the Royal College of Art; F.M.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Simpson, Robert Anning Bell and C.J.Allen were respectively professor of architecture, instructor in painting and design, and instructor in sculpture at Liverpool School of Art; Robert Catterson-Smith, the headmaster of the Birmingham Art School from 1902 to 1920, was also an AWG member; W.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Lethaby and George Frampton were inspectors and advisors to the London County Council's (LCC) education board and in 1896, largely as a result of their work, the LCC set up the Central School of Arts and Crafts and made them joint principals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Until the formation of the Bauhaus in Germany, the Central School was regarded as the most progressive art school in Europe.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Shortly after its foundation, the Camberwell School of Arts and Crafts was set up on Arts and Crafts lines by the local borough council.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] As head of the Royal College of Art in 1898, Crane tried to reform it along more practical lines, but resigned after a year, defeated by the bureaucracy of the Board of Education, who then appointed Augustus Spencer to implement his plan.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Spencer brought in Lethaby to head its school of design and several members of the Art Workers' Guild as teachers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Ten years after reform, a committee of inquiry reviewed the RCA and found that it was still not adequately training students for industry.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] In the debate that followed the publication of the committee's report, C.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Ashbee published a highly critical essay, *Should We Stop Teaching Art*, in which he called for the system of art education to be completely dismantled and for the crafts to be learned in state-subsidised workshops instead.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Lewis Foreman Day, an important figure in the Arts and Crafts movement, took a different view in his dissenting report to the committee of inquiry, arguing for greater emphasis on principles of design against the growing orthodoxy of teaching design by direct working in materials.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Nevertheless, the Arts and Crafts ethos thoroughly pervaded British art schools and persisted, in the view of the historian of art education, Stuart MacDonald, until after the Second World War.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff was the first municipality to incorporate within a Canadian national park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The town is a member of the Calgary Regional Partnership.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff is one of Canada's most popular tourist destinations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Known for its mountainous surroundings and hot springs, it is a destination for outdoor sports and hiking, biking, scrambling and skiing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Sunshine Village, Ski Norquay and Lake Louise Ski Resort are nearby ski resorts within the national park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The area was named Banff in 1884 by George Stephen, president of the Canadian Pacific Railway, recalling his birthplace near Banff, Scotland.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The Canadian Pacific built a series of grand hotels along the rail line and advertised the Banff Springs Hotel as an international tourist resort.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The site of Banff has been continually inhabited by First Nations for at least 10,000 years.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The town's location was the site of an Interior Salishan settlement, which was both a wintering village and a trading post.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Nakoda and Blackfoot peoples have also, at various points, lived at and near the present location.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The town of Banff was first established in the 1880s after the transcontinental railway was built through the Bow Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1883, three Canadian Pacific Railway workers stumbled upon a series of natural hot springs on the side of Sulphur Mountain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1885, Canada established a federal reserve of 26 km2 (10 sq mi) around the Cave and Basin hot springs and began promoting the area as an international resort and spa as a way to support the new railway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1887, the reserve area was increased to 673 km2 (260 sq mi) and named "Rocky Mountain Park".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] This was the beginning of Canada's National Park system.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The Banff townsite was developed near the railway station as a service centre for tourists visiting the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Services, such as St George-in-the-Pines church, were constructed through the late 19th century.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] It was administered by the Government of Canada's national parks system until 1990 when the Town of Banff became the only incorporated municipality within a Canadian national park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] An internment camp was set up at Banff and Castle Mountain in Dominion Park from July 1915 to July 1917, mostly imprisoning Ukrainian immigrants.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The prisoners of the internment camp were used as slave labour to build the infrastructure of the national park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1985, the United Nations declared Banff National Park, as one of the Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, a UNESCO world heritage site.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff remains one of the most popular tourist destinations in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] One of the most notable figures of Banff was Norman Luxton, who was known as "Mr.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] He published the *Crag and Canyon* newspaper, built the King Edward Hotel and the Lux Theatre, and founded the Sign of the Goat Curio Shop, which led to the development of the Luxton Museum of Plains Indians, now the Buffalo Nations Museum.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] He and his family helped organize the Banff Indian Days and the Banff Winter Carnival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1976, the International Astronomical Union's Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature (IAU/WGPSN) adopted the name *Banff* for a crater on Mars, after the town in Alberta.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The crater is at latitude 17.7° north and longitude 30.8° west.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In 1991, Banff hosted the 1991 Winter Deaflympics, the first and only year that the Deaflympics was hosted in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, the town temporarily closed portions of its main street to vehicle traffic to create a downtown pedestrian zone.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The Banff Town Council said the pedestrian zone would stay in effect until at least 2023.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The town is surrounded by mountains, notably Mount Rundle, Sulphur Mountain, Mount Norquay, and Cascade Mountain, and is situated above Bow Falls near the confluence of the Bow River and Spray River.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Soils are calcareous and usually imperfectly to poorly drained in their natural state with textures from very fine sandy loam to silty clay loam.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff experiences a subarctic climate (Köppen climate classification *Dfc*) that borders on a humid continental climate (Köppen *Dfb*).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Winter temperatures range from an average low of −13.5 °C (7.7 °F) to an average high of −0.5 °C (31.1 °F).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Summer temperatures in the warmest month are an average high of 22.5 °C (72.5 °F) and an average low of 6.8 °C (44.2 °F).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Snow has been recorded in all months of the year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The annual snowfall averages 183.8 cm (72.4 in).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The highest temperature ever recorded was 37.8 °C (100 °F) on June 29, 2021, during the 2021 Western North America heat wave.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In the 2021 Canadian census conducted by Statistics Canada, the Town of Banff had a population of 8,305 living in 2,930 of its 3,287 total private dwellings, a change of 5.8% from its 2016 population of 7,851.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] With a land area of 4.08 km2 (1.58 sq mi), it had a population density of 2,035.5/km2 in 2021.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The population of the Town of Banff according to its 2017 municipal census is 8,875, an increase of 5.4% from its 2014 municipal census population of 8,421.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In the Canada 2016 Census conducted by Statistics Canada, the Town of Banff recorded a population of 7,851 living in 2,543 of its 2,729 total private dwellings, a 3.5% change from its 2011 population of 7,584.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] With a land area of 4.77 km2 (1.84 sq mi), Banff had a population density of 1,645.9/km2 in 2016.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Parks Canada enforces requirements that individuals must meet to reside in the town, in order "to ensure that a broad supply of housing types are available for those who work and raise families in the community".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Several mountains are located immediately adjacent to the townsite, including Mount Rundle (2,949 m (9,675 ft)); Cascade Mountain (2,998 m (9,836 ft)); and Mount Norquay (2,134 m (7,001 ft)).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Mount Norquay has a ski slope as well as mountain biking trails on the Stoney Squaw portion, and Via Ferrata (an assisted climbing experience).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] A tourist attraction, the Banff Gondola, is available to ascend Sulphur Mountain (2,281 m (7,484 ft)) where a boardwalk (Banff Skywalk) beginning from the upper terminal connects to Sanson Peak.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Sulphur Mountain is also the location of the Banff Upper Hot Springs.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Lake Minnewanka located six minutes north of the townsite is a day-use area with a variety of activities.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Mountain biking, hiking, and fishing are allowed in this part of the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] A Lake Cruise, motor boat rentals, and a small food concession are available at the marina.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Tunnel Mountain (formerly known as Sleeping Buffalo Mountain) (1,690 m (5,540 ft)) is situated within the townsite and has a summit that can be scaled in less than half an hour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] It was named Tunnel Mountain because surveyors initially wanted to make a tunnel for the Canadian Pacific Railway right through the mountain, instead of following the Bow River Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Located on the side of Tunnel Mountain is the Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity, which hosts events, including outdoor concerts, dance, opera, and theatre.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff is home to the Banff World Television Festival, Banff Mountain Film Festival, Rocky Mountain Music Festival, and Bike Fest.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The town is also the starting point of the 4,417 km (2,745 mi) Great Divide Mountain Bike Route, which terminates at Antelope Wells, New Mexico in the United States.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff and nearby Canmore played host to the 2014 Alberta Winter Games.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff also hosted the 1991 Winter Deaflympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] For several years there has been an annual long-distance relay run between Banff and Jasper, Alberta (formerly known as the Jasper to Banff Relay).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Banff has a long history of hosting Team Canada hockey training camps, including Canada's 2012 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships team when the event was held in Alberta and the 1984 Canada Cup squad which practiced there, before the start of the tournament.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In June 2008, the Banff council launched a local bus system called Roam, with three routes connecting the town, Tunnel Mountain, the Banff Springs Hotel, and the Banff Gondola.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The service is operated using four hybrid Nova buses, each decorated with scenes from the National Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Many bus stops along the routes have screens that tell passengers exactly how many minutes before the next two buses arrive.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In December 2012, the bus system was expanded to include the hourly Route 3 service between Banff and Canmore.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] As of January 2024, Roam Transit offers 10 routes, the majority serving destinations within Banff or to national park locations nearby.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] In addition, Roam also offers two routes to Lake Louise, as well as a local service route within Canmore.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The railway came to Banff when the Canadian Pacific Railway (CPR) line from Calgary opened in 1883.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The current station building was opened by the CPR in 1910, and was declared a heritage railway station by the Canadian federal government in 1991.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Via Rail long-distance trains no longer serve Banff, but the railway station remains in use by the Rocky Mountaineer and Royal Canadian Pacific tour trains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] The nearest airport to Banff with major service is the Calgary International Airport in Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-alberta] Acute health care is provided at the Banff – Mineral Springs Hospital.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The mountains were formed from sedimentary rocks that were pushed east over newer rock strata, between 80 million and 55 million years ago.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Over the past few million years, glaciers have at times covered most of the park; today they are found only on the mountain slopes, though they include the Columbia Icefield, the largest uninterrupted glacial mass in the Rockies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Erosion from water and ice have carved the mountains into their current shapes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Archaeological evidence at Vermilion Lakes indicates presence of Indigenous peoples for more than 10,000 years in the Banff area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Canadian Pacific Railway was instrumental in Banff's early years, building the Banff Springs Hotel and Chateau Lake Louise, and attracting tourists through extensive advertising.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the early 20th century, roads were built in Banff, at times by war internees from World War I, and through Great Depression-era public works projects.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Icefields Parkway extends from Lake Louise, connecting to Jasper National Park in the north.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since the 1960s, park accommodations have been open all year, with annual tourism visits to Banff increasing to over 5 million in the 1990s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Millions more pass through the park on the Trans-Canada Highway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] As Banff has over three million visitors annually, the health of its ecosystem has been threatened.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the mid-1990s, Parks Canada responded by initiating a two-year study which resulted in management recommendations and new policies that aim to preserve ecological integrity.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park has a subarctic climate with three ecoregions, including montane, subalpine, and alpine.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The forests are dominated by lodgepole pine at lower elevations and Engelmann spruce in higher ones below the treeline, above which is primarily rocks and ice.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Mammal species such as the grizzly bear, cougar, wolverine, elk, bighorn sheep and moose are found, along with hundreds of bird species.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Reptiles and amphibians are also found, but only a limited number of species have been recorded.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Throughout its history, Banff National Park has been shaped by tension between conservationist and land exploitation interests.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park was established on November 25, 1885, as Banff Hot Springs Reserve, in response to conflicting claims over who discovered hot springs there and who had the right to develop the hot springs for commercial interests.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The conservationists prevailed when Prime Minister John A.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Macdonald set aside the hot springs as a small protected reserve, which was later expanded to include Lake Louise and other areas extending north to the Columbia Icefield.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Archaeological evidence found at Vermilion Lakes indicates the first human activity in Banff to 10,300 BP.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Prior to European contact, the area that is now Banff National Park was home to many Indigenous Peoples, including the Stoney Nakoda, Ktunaxa, Tsuut'ina, Kainaiwa, Piikani, Siksika, and Plains Cree.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Indigenous peoples utilized the area to hunt, fish, trade, travel, survey and practice culture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Many areas within Banff National Park are still known by their Stoney Nakoda names such as Lake Minnewanka and the Waputik Range.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Cave and Basin served as an important cultural and spiritual site for the Stoney Nakoda.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With the admission of British Columbia to Canada on July 20, 1871, Canada agreed to build a transcontinental railroad.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Construction of the railroad began in 1875, with Kicking Horse Pass chosen, over the more northerly Yellowhead Pass, as the route through the Canadian Rockies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Ten years later, on November 7, 1885, the last spike was driven in Craigellachie, British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With conflicting claims over the discovery of hot springs in Banff, Prime Minister John A.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Macdonald decided to set aside a small reserve of 26 square kilometres (10 sq mi) around the hot springs at Cave and Basin as a public park known as the *Banff Hot Springs Reserve* in 1885.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Under the *Rocky Mountains Park Act*, enacted on June 23, 1887, the park was expanded to 674 km2 (260 sq mi) and named *Rocky Mountains Park*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This was Canada's first national park, and the third established in North America, after Yellowstone and Mackinac National Parks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Canadian Pacific Railway built the Banff Springs Hotel and Lake Louise Chalet to attract tourists and increase the number of rail passengers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Stoney Nakoda First Nation were removed from Banff National Park between the years 1890 and 1920.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park was designed to appeal to sportsmen, and tourists.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The exclusionary policy met the goals of sports hunting, tourism, and game conservation, as well as of those attempting to "civilize" the First Nations of the area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Early on, Banff was popular with wealthy European and American tourists, the former of which arrived in Canada via trans-Atlantic luxury liner and continued westward on the railroad.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Some visitors participated in mountaineering activities, often hiring local guides.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Guides Jim and Bill Brewster founded one of the first outfitters in Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] From 1906, the Alpine Club of Canada organized climbs, hikes and camps in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] By 1911, Banff was accessible by automobile from Calgary.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Beginning in 1916, the Brewsters offered motorcoach tours of Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1920, access to Lake Louise by road was available, and the Banff-Windermere Road opened in 1923 to connect Banff with British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1902, the park was expanded to cover 11,400 km2 (4,400 sq mi), encompassing areas around Lake Louise, and the Bow, Red Deer, Kananaskis, and Spray rivers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bowing to pressure from grazing and logging interests, the size of the park was reduced in 1911 to 4,663 km2 (1,800 sq mi), eliminating many eastern foothills areas from the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Park boundaries changed several more times up until 1930, when the area of Banff was fixed at 6,697 km2 (2,586 sq mi), with the passage of the *National Parks Act*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The act, which took effect May 30, 1930, also renamed the park *Banff National Park*, named for the Canadian Pacific Railway station, which in turn was named after the Banffshire region in Scotland.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With the construction of a new east gate in 1933, Alberta transferred 0.84 km2 (0.32 sq mi) to the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This, along with other minor changes in the park boundaries in 1949, set the area of the park at 6,641 km2 (2,564 sq mi).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1877, the First Nations of the area signed Treaty 7, which gave Canada rights to explore the land for resources.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] At the beginning of the 20th century, coal was mined near Lake Minnewanka in Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] For a brief period, a mine operated at Anthracite but was shut down in 1904.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Bankhead mine, at Cascade Mountain, was operated by the Canadian Pacific Railway from 1903 to 1922.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1926, the town was dismantled, with many buildings moved to the town of Banff and elsewhere.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] During World War I, immigrants from Austria-Hungary and Germany were sent to Banff to work in internment camps.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The main camp was at Castle Mountain, and was moved to Cave and Basin during winter.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Much early infrastructure and road construction was done by men of various Slavic origins although Ukrainians constituted a majority of those held in Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1931, the Government of Canada enacted the *Unemployment and Farm Relief Act* which provided public works projects in the national parks during the Great Depression.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In Banff, workers constructed a new bathhouse and pool at Upper Hot Springs to supplement Cave and Basin.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Other projects involved road building in the park, tasks around the Banff townsite and construction of a highway connecting Banff and Jasper.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1934, the*Public Works Construction Act* was passed, providing continued funding for the public works projects.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] New projects included construction of a new registration facility at Banff's east gate and construction of an administrative building in Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] By 1940, the Icefields Parkway reached the Columbia Icefield area of Banff and connected Banff and Jasper.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Most of the infrastructure present in the national park dates from public work projects enacted during the Great Depression.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Alternative service camps for conscientious objectors were set up in Banff during World War II, with camps at Lake Louise, Stoney Creek, and Healy Creek.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] These camps were largely populated by Mennonites from Saskatchewan.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Winter tourism in Banff began in February 1917, with the first Banff Winter Carnival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] It was marketed to a regional middle class audience, and became the centerpiece of local boosters aiming to attract visitors, which were a low priority for the Canadian Pacific Railway (CPR).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The carnival featured a large ice palace, which in 1917 was built by World War I internees.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Carnival events included cross-country skiing, ski jumping, curling, snowshoe, and skijoring.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the 1930s, the first downhill ski resort, Sunshine Village, was developed by the Brewsters.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Mount Norquay ski area was also developed during the 1930s, with the first chair lift installed there in 1948.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since 1968, when the Banff Springs Hotel was winterized, Banff has been a year-round destination.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the 1950s, the Trans-Canada Highway was constructed, providing another transportation corridor through the Bow Valley, making the park more accessible.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Canada launched several bids to host the Winter Olympics in Banff, with the first bid for the 1964 Winter Olympics, which were eventually awarded to Innsbruck, Austria.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Canada narrowly lost a second bid, for the 1968 Winter Olympics, which were awarded to Grenoble, France.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Once again, Banff launched a bid to host the 1972 Winter Olympics, with plans to hold the Olympics at Lake Louise.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The 1972 bid was controversial, as environmental lobby groups strongly opposed the bid, which had sponsorship from Imperial Oil.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bowing to pressure, Jean Chrétien, then the Minister of Environment, the government department responsible for Parks Canada, withdrew support for the bid, which was eventually lost to Sapporo, Japan.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] When nearby Calgary hosted the 1988 Winter Olympics, the cross-country ski events were held at the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park at Canmore, Alberta, located just outside the eastern gates of Banff National Park on the Trans-Canada Highway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since the original Rocky Mountains Park Act, subsequent acts and policies placed greater emphasis on conservation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With public sentiment tending towards environmentalism, Parks Canada issued major new policy in 1979, which emphasized conservation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The *National Parks Act* was amended in 1988, which made preserving ecological integrity the first priority in all park management decisions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The act also required each park to produce a management plan, with greater public participation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With this designation came added obligations for conservation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] During the 1980s, Parks Canada moved to privatize many park services such as golf courses, and added user fees for use of other facilities and services to help deal with budget cuts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1990, the town of Banff was incorporated, giving local residents more say regarding any proposed developments.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the 1990s, development plans for the park, including expansion at Sunshine Village, were under fire with lawsuits filed by Canadian Parks and Wilderness Society (CPAWS).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the mid-1990s, the Banff–Bow Valley Study was initiated to find ways to better address environmental concerns, and issues relating to development in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is in the Rocky Mountains on Alberta's western border with British Columbia in the Alberta Mountain forests ecoregion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] By road, the town of Banff is 128 kilometres (80 mi) west of Calgary and 401 km (249 mi) southwest of Edmonton.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Jasper National Park borders Banff National Park to the north, while Yoho National Park is to the west and Kootenay National Park is to the south.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Kananaskis Country, which includes Bow Valley Wildland Provincial Park, Spray Valley Provincial Park, and Peter Lougheed Provincial Park, is located to the south and east of Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway passes through Banff National Park, from the eastern boundary near Canmore, through the towns of Banff and Lake Louise, and into Yoho National Park in British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Banff townsite is the main commercial centre in the national park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The village of Lake Louise is at the junction of the Trans-Canada Highway and the Icefields Parkway, which extends north to the Jasper townsite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff, established in 1885, is the main commercial centre in Banff National Park, as well as a centre for cultural activities.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff is home to several cultural institutions, including the Banff Centre, the Whyte Museum, the Buffalo Nations Luxton Museum, Cave and Basin National Historic Site, and several art galleries.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Throughout its history, Banff has hosted many annual events, including Banff Indian Days which began in 1889, and the Banff Winter Carnival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since 1976, The Banff Centre has organized the Banff Mountain Film Festival.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1990, Banff incorporated as a town of Alberta, though still subject to the *National Parks Act* and federal authority in regards to planning and development.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In its 2014 census, the town of Banff had a permanent population of 8,421 as well as 965 non-permanent residents for a total population of 9,386.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Bow River flows through the town of Banff, with the Bow Falls on the outskirts of town.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Lake Louise, a hamlet 54 km (34 mi) northwest of the town of Banff, is home to the landmark Chateau Lake Louise at the edge of Lake Louise.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Located 15 km (9.3 mi) from Lake Louise, Moraine Lake provides a scenic vista of the Valley of the Ten Peaks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This scene is on the back of the Canadian $20 bill in the 1969–1979 ("Scenes of Canada") series.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Lake Louise Mountain Resort is also near the village.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Lake Louise is one of the most visited lakes in the world and is framed to the southwest by the Mount Victoria Glacier.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Icefields Parkway is a 230-kilometre-long (140 mi) road connecting Lake Louise to Jasper, Alberta.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Parkway originates at Lake Louise, and extends north up the Bow Valley, past Hector Lake, which is the largest natural lake in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Other scenic lakes near the parkway include Bow Lake, and Peyto Lakes, both north of Hector Lake.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Parkway then crosses Bow Summit (2,088 m (6,850 ft)), and follows the Mistaya River to Saskatchewan Crossing, where it converges with the Howse and North Saskatchewan River.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bow Summit is the highest elevation crossed by a public road in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The North Saskatchewan River flows east from Saskatchewan Crossing, out of Banff, into what is known as David Thompson Country, and onto Edmonton.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The David Thompson Highway follows the North Saskatchewan River, past the man-made Abraham Lake, and through David Thompson Country.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] North of Saskatchewan Crossing, the Icefields Parkway follows the North Saskatchewan River up to the Columbia Icefield.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Parkway crosses into Jasper National Park at Sunwapta Pass at 2,035 metres (6,677 ft) in elevation, and continues on from there to the Jasper townsite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies consist of several northwest–southeast trending ranges.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Two main mountain ranges are within the park, each consisting of numerous subranges.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The western border of the park follows the crest of the Main Ranges (also known as the *Park Ranges*), which is also the continental divide.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Main Ranges in Banff National Park include from north to south, the Waputik, Bow and Blue Ranges.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The high peaks west of Lake Louise are part of the Bow Range.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The eastern border of the park includes all of the Front Ranges consisting of from north to south, the Palliser, Sawback and Sundance Ranges.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Banff townsite is in the Front Ranges.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Just outside the park to the east lie the foothills that extend from Canmore at the eastern entrance of the park eastward into the Great Plains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Well west of the park, the Western Ranges of the Rockies pass through Yoho and Kootenay National Parks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Though the tallest peak entirely within the park is Mount Forbes at 3,612 metres (11,850 ft), Mount Assiniboine on the Banff-Mount Assiniboine Provincial Park border is slightly higher at 3,618 m (11,870 ft).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies are composed of sedimentary rock, including shale, sandstone, dolomite and limestone.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The vast majority of geologic formations in Banff range in age from Precambrian to the Jurassic periods (600–145 m.y.a.).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] However, rocks as young as the lower Cretaceous (145–66 m.y.a.) can be found near the east entrance and on Cascade Mountain above the Banff townsite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] These sedimentary rocks formed at the bottom of shallow seas between 600 and 175 m.y.a. and were pushed east during the Laramide orogeny.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Mountain building in Banff National Park ended approximately 55 m.y.a.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies may have risen up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) approximately 70 m.y.a.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Once mountain formation ceased, erosion carved the mountains into their present rugged shape.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The erosion was first due to water, then was greatly accelerated by the Quaternary glaciation 2.5 million years ago.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Glacial landforms dominate Banff's geomorphology, with examples of all classic glacial forms, including cirques, arêtes, hanging valleys, moraines, and U-shaped valleys.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The pre-existing structure left over from mountain-building strongly guided glacial erosion: mountains in Banff include complex, irregular, anticlinal, synclinal, castellate, dogtooth, and sawback mountains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Many of the mountain ranges trend northwest to southeast, with sedimentary layering dipping down to the west at 40–60 degrees.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This leads to dip slope landforms, with generally steeper east and north faces, and trellis drainage, where rivers and old glacial valleys followed the weaker layers in the rocks as they were relatively easily weathered and eroded.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Classic examples are found at the Banff townsite proper: Mount Rundle is a classic dip slope mountain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Just to the north of the Banff townsite, Castle Mountain is composed of numerous Cambrian age rock formations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The uppermost section of the peak consists of relatively harder dolomite from the Eldon Formation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Below that lies the less dense shales of the Stephen Formation and the lowest exposed cliffs are limestones of the Cathedral Formation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Dogtooth mountains, such as Mount Louis, exhibit sharp, jagged slopes.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Sawback Range, which consists of nearly vertical dipping sedimentary layers, has been eroded by cross gullies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The erosion of these almost vertical layers of rock strata in the Sawback Range has resulted in formations that appear like the teeth on a saw blade.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Erosion and deposition of higher elevation rock layers has resulted in scree deposits at the lowest elevations of many of the mountains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park has numerous large glaciers and icefields, 100 of which can be observed from the Icefields Parkway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Small cirque glaciers are fairly common in the Main Ranges, in depressions on the side of many mountains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] As with the majority of mountain glaciers around the world, the glaciers in Banff are retreating.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] While Peyto Glacier is one of the longest continuously studied glaciers in the world, with research extending back to the 1970s, most of the glaciers of the Canadian Rockies have only been scientifically evaluated since the late 1990s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Glaciologists are now researching the glaciers in the park more thoroughly, and have been analyzing the impact that reduced glacier ice may have on water supplies to streams and rivers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Estimates are that 150 glaciers disappeared in the Canadian Rockies (areas both inside and outside Banff National Park) between 1920 and 1985.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Another 150 glaciers disappeared between 1985 and 2005, indicating that the retreat and disappearance of glaciers is accelerating.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In Banff National Park alone, in 1985 there were 365 glaciers but by 2005, 29 glaciers had disappeared.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The total glaciated area dropped from 625 to 500 square kilometres (241 to 193 sq mi) in that time period.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The largest glaciated areas include the Waputik and Wapta Icefields, which both lie on the Banff-Yoho National Park border.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Outlets of the Wapta Icefield on the Banff side of the continental divide include Peyto, Bow, and Vulture Glaciers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bow Glacier retreated an estimated 1,100 m (3,600 ft) between the years 1850 and 1953, and since that period, there has been further retreat which has left a newly formed lake at the terminal moraine.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Peyto Glacier has lost 70 percent of its volume since record keeping began and retreated approximately 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) between 1999 and 2021.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Peyto Glacier is at risk of losing 80-90% of its current mass by 2100.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Columbia Icefield, at the northern end of Banff, straddles the Banff and Jasper National Park border and extends into British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Snow Dome, in the Columbia Icefield is a hydrological apex of North America, with water flowing via outlet glaciers to the Atlantic, Pacific and Arctic Oceans.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Saskatchewan Glacier, which is approximately 13 km (8 mi) in length and 30 km2 (12 sq mi) in area, is the major outlet of the Columbia Icefield that flows into Banff National Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Between the years 1893 and 1953, Saskatchewan Glacier had retreated a distance of 1,364 m (4,475 ft), with the rate of retreat between 1948 and 1953 averaging 55 m (180 ft) per year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Overall, the glaciers of the Canadian Rockies lost 25 percent of their mass during the 20th century.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Under the Köppen climate classification, the park has a subarctic climate (*Dfc*) with cold, snowy winters, and mild summers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The climate is influenced by altitude with lower temperatures generally found at higher elevations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Located on the eastern side of the Continental Divide, Banff National Park receives 454.0 mm (17.87 in) of precipitation annually.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This is considerably less than in Yoho National Park on the western side of the divide in British Columbia, where 884.2 mm (34.81 in) (1971-1990 normals) is received at Wapta Lake and approximately 1,282 mm (50.5 in) at Boulder Creek annually.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Being influenced by altitude, snowfall is also greater at higher elevations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] As such, 183.8 cm (72.4 in) (1991–2020 normals) of snow falls on average each year in the Banff townsite, while 279.1 cm (109.9 in) (1981-2010 normals) falls in Lake Louise, which is at a higher altitude, 1,524 m (5,000 ft).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] During winter months, temperatures in Banff are moderated, compared to other areas of central and northern Alberta, due to Chinook winds and other influences from British Columbia.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The mean low temperature during January is −13.5 °C (7.7 °F), and the mean high temperature is −3.5 °C (25.7 °F) for the town of Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] However, temperatures can drop below −20 °C (−4 °F) with wind chill values dropping below −30 for 3.5 days in an average year.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Weather conditions during summer months are warm, with high temperatures during July averaging 22.5 °C (72.5 °F), and daily low temperatures averaging 6.8 °C (44.2 °F), leading to a large diurnal range owing to the relative dryness of the air.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park spans three ecoregions, including montane, subalpine, and alpine.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The subalpine ecoregion, which consists mainly of dense forest, comprises 53 percent of Banff's area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] 27 percent of the park is located above the tree line, in the alpine ecoregion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The tree line in Banff lies approximately at 2,300 m (7,500 ft), with open meadows at alpine regions and some areas covered by glaciers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A small portion (3 percent) of the park, at lower elevations, is in the montane ecoregion.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Lodgepole pine forests dominate the montane region of Banff, with Engelmann spruce, willow, aspen, occasional Douglas-fir and a few Douglas maple interspersed.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Engelmann spruce are more common in the subalpine regions of Banff, with some areas of lodgepole pine, and subalpine fir.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The montane areas in the Bow Valley, which tend to be the preferred habitat for wildlife, have been subjected to significant human development over the years.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park has 56 recorded mammal species.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears and black bears inhabit the forested regions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Cougar, lynx, wolverine, red fox, weasel, river otter, coyote, and grey wolf are the primary predatory mammals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Elk, mule deer, and white-tailed deer are common in the valleys of the park, including around (and sometimes in) the Banff townsite, while moose tend to be more elusive, sticking primarily to wetland areas and near streams.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the alpine regions, mountain goat, bighorn sheep, marmot and pika are widespread.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Other mammals such as beaver, porcupine, squirrel, chipmunk, snowshoe hare, and Columbian ground squirrel are the more commonly observed smaller mammals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Caribou were the rarest large mammals in the park, but an avalanche in 2009 may have killed the last five remaining within park boundaries.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The American bison was extirpated in Banff, but was brought back to the park in 2017, and one free-roaming herd lives within the protected area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Due to the harsh winters, the park has few reptile and amphibian species with only one species of toad, three species of frog, one salamander species and two species of snakes that have been identified.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] At least 280 species of birds can be found in Banff including bald and golden eagles, red-tailed hawk, osprey, and merlin, all of which are predatory species.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Additionally, commonly seen species such as the Canada jay, American three-toed woodpecker, mountain bluebird, Clark's nutcracker, mountain chickadee and pipit are frequently found in the lower elevations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The white-tailed ptarmigan is a ground bird that is often seen in the alpine zones.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Rivers and lakes are frequented by over a hundred different species including loon, heron and mallard which spend their summers in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Endangered species in Banff include the Banff Springs snail (*Physella johnsoni*) that is found in the hot springs of Banff, and the woodland caribou.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Mountain pine beetles have caused a number of large-scale infestations in Banff National Park, feeding on the phloem of mature lodgepole pines.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Alberta's first known outbreak occurred in 1940, infecting 43 km2 (17 sq mi) of forest in Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A second major outbreak occurred in the late 1970s and early 1980s in Banff and the surrounding Rocky Mountains region.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is the most visited Alberta tourist destination and one of the most visited national parks in North America, with more than three million tourists annually.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Tourism in Banff contributes an estimated CA$6 billion annually to the economy.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A park pass is required for stopping in the park, and permit checks are common during the summer months, especially at Lake Louise and the start of the Icefields Parkway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A permit is not required if travelling straight through the park without stopping.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Approximately 5 million people pass through Banff annually on the Trans-Canada Highway without stopping.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 2009, Banff Lake Louise Tourism hoped the appearance of the "Crasher Squirrel" internet meme would stimulate interest in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is managed by Parks Canada, under the *National Parks Act* which was passed in 1930.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Over time, park management policies have increasingly emphasized environmental protection over development.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1964, a policy statement was issued that reiterated ideals of conservation laid out in the 1930 act.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With the controversial bid for the 1972 Winter Olympics, environmental groups became more influential, leading Parks Canada to withdraw its support for the bid.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The 1979 Beaver Book was a major new policy, which emphasized conservation.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1988, the *National Parks Act* was amended, making the maintenance of ecological integrity the top priority.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The amendment also paved the way for non-governmental organizations to challenge Parks Canada in court, for breaches in adhering to the act.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1994, Parks Canada established revised "Guiding Principles and Operating Policies", which included a mandate for the Banff–Bow Valley Study to draft management recommendations.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] As with other national parks, Banff is required to have a Park Management Plan.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] On a provincial level, the park area and the included communities (other than the town of Banff which is an incorporated municipality) are administered by Alberta Municipal Affairs as Improvement District No.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park was originally considered as a recreational area for visitors offering multiple leisure activities – the original wildlife policy viewed wildlife in Banff only as game or pests up until the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] As ecological awareness increased, management procedures expanded with the inclusion of public participation in many management decisions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Simultaneously, the increase in human construction (such as new highways) on the natural landscape increased the frequency of human–animal conflicts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1988 wildlife began to be considered an integral part of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park now has a number of wildlife management strategies that aim to conserve certain species.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Parks Canada uses an ecosystem based management approach that aims to preserve the ecology of the park while still providing for visitors.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Management decisions are based on modern scientific ecological information as well as traditional knowledge.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Elk are a very important species in Banff National Park, partly because they represent a source of food for declining wolves.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] However they also have harsh impacts on the environment.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Large elk populations cause vegetation degradation, human–animal conflicts and destabilization of biological interactions.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1999, the implementation of the Banff National Park Elk Management Strategy by Parks Canada and the Elk Advisory Committee aimed to monitor and control the population to decrease conflicts and aid ecological process recovery.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Elk handling facilities are areas of pens with loading and unloading ramps where water and food are provided to the elk.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] They were created to help reduce herd numbers by increasing wariness and encouraging migratory behaviour, deterring the elk from the town of Banff.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] These measures allowed more predator–prey interactions thanks to the creation of corridors.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] They also increased elk migration, restored the willow and aspen communities and highlighted the primary role of wolves in elk population management.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The state of grizzly bear populations in Banff is seen as a proxy for ecological integrity.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] To keep bears away from humans, an electric fence was put up around the summer gondola and parking lot at Lake Louise in 2001.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bear-proof garbage cans, which do not allow bears to access their contents, help to deter them from human sites.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The fruit of buffaloberry bushes is eaten by bears, so the bushes have been removed in some areas where the risk of a bear–human encounter is high.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Aversive conditioning deters bears by modifying their behaviour.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Deterrents such as noise makers and rubber bullets are used each time the bear performs an undesirable action.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Advice is also given to people to avoid an eventual habituation of bears to human presence.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] If this conditioning is continual the bear will be less likely to continue the undesirable behaviour (crossing into campsites and roads etc.).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Southern mountain caribou management previously aimed to identify what was threatening caribou populations and find solutions to mitigate the threats, but the last caribou in the park was found dead in an avalanche in 2009.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] There was concern over why more had not been done to save the caribou population.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The primary reason for their decline is thought to have been habitat loss and altered predator–prey dynamics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Park management began monitoring the last five caribou in the park in 2002 and taking actions such as reducing impacts of humans, conducting studies of the population, and investigating the possibility of translocating caribou to increase the Banff population.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In the mid-1980s gray wolves recolonized the Bow Valley in Banff National Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] They had been absent for 30 years due to systematic predator control hunting which began in 1850.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Wolves filtered back to Banff and recolonized one zone of the Bow Valley in 1985 and another in 1991.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A high level of human use surrounding a third zone at Banff townsite has deterred the wolves from that area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The wolves are important in controlling elk populations and improve the balance of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A routine park study to monitor the wolves in Banff has now grown into the Southern Rockies Canine Project – the largest wolf research project in North America.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The estimated wolf population in Banff National Park and the surrounding areas is now 60–70 animals.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Plains bison were reintroduced to Banff in 2017.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The park has an extensive system of grasslands in backcountry valleys that are perfect for the bison.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] 16 bison were translocated from Elk Island National Park and initially placed under observation for a year in an enclosed pasture within a 1,200 square kilometres (460 sq mi) reintroduction site near Panther River Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] After 18 months of acclimation, the herd was released into the reintroduction site and as of August 2021, the herd had grown to 66.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Wildlife crossings have been successful in Banff National Park at reducing the number of animals killed on the roads.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] There is also 82 kilometres (51 mi) of fencing at the edge of the highway in the park to prevent animals from getting onto the roads.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since it was put up, this has reduced collisions between wildlife and vehicles by over 80 per cent.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Train tracks still pose challenges to conservationists.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Many bears have been killed by trains, often because they are attracted to grain spills along the tracks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Transportation corridors provide openings for plants which are also utilized by bears.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A partnership between Parks Canada and Canadian Pacific Railway allowed the creation of the first Railway-Bear Conflict Mitigation Symposium in 2010.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Initiatives included building wooden pegboards to fence off the sides of tracks and chemically treating grains to deter the bears.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] After a complete review of the research projects, the development of some of them has been authorized, including grain alteration and the use of cameras to study the behavioural response of bears to trains.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 2011, Parks Canada began to study the effectiveness of electro-mats, large mats that give a small electric shock to animals that step on them, as a potential deterrent around train tracks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] A trial instalment of the mats was placed in Banff to test their effectiveness in deterring animals like bears from gaining access to the fenced train tracks inside the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] General prohibitions implemented to ensure wildlife respect include the prohibition of feeding, touching, or holding animals in captivity, and the disturbance or destruction of bird nests.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since the 19th century, humans have impacted Banff's environment through introduction of non-native species, controls on other species, and development in the Bow Valley, among other human activities.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Bison once lived in the valleys of Banff and were hunted by indigenous people, but the last bison were killed off in 1850s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 2017 a small herd of sixteen plains bison were reintroduced into an eastern section of the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Elk are not indigenous to Banff, and were introduced in 1917 with 57 elk brought in from Yellowstone National Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The introduction of elk to Banff, combined with controls on coyote and wolves by Parks Canada beginning in the 1930s, has caused imbalance of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Other species that have been displaced from the Bow Valley include grizzly bears, cougars, lynx, wolverine, otter, and moose.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Beginning in 1985, gray wolves were recolonizing areas in the Bow Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] However, the wolf population has struggled, with 32 wolf deaths along the Trans-Canada Highway between 1987 and 2000, leaving only 31 wolves in the area.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The population of bull trout and other native species of fish in Banff's lakes has also dwindled, with the introduction of non-native species including brook trout, and rainbow trout.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Lake trout, westslope cutthroat trout, and chiselmouth are rare native species, while chinook salmon, white sturgeon, Pacific lamprey, and Banff longnose dace are likely extirpated locally.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Banff longnose dace, once only found in Banff, is now an extinct species.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway, passing through Banff, has been problematic, posing hazards for wildlife due to vehicle traffic and as an impediment to wildlife migration.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears are among the species impacted by the highway, which together with other developments in Banff, has caused fragmentation of the landscape.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears prefer the montane habitat, which has been most impacted by development.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Wildlife crossings, including a series of underpasses, and six wildlife overpasses, have been constructed at a number of points along the Trans-Canada Highway to help alleviate this problem.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Parks Canada management practices, notably fire suppression, since Banff National Park was established have impacted the park's ecosystem.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Since 1983, Parks Canada has adopted a strategy that employed prescribed burns, which helps to mimic effects of natural fires.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is bisected by two highways that cross the Alberta/British Columbia border while another provides a third access within Alberta.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway (Highway 1) bisects the park in an east–west direction, connecting it to Vancouver to the west and Calgary to the east.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Highway 93 bisects the park in a north–south direction, connecting it to Cranbrook to the south and Jasper to the north.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The portion of Highway 93 north of Lake Louise is known as the Icefields Parkway whereas the portion southwest of Castle Junction is known as the Banff-Windermere Parkway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Highway 11 (the David Thompson Highway) connects the Icefields Parkway at Saskatchewan River Crossing to Rocky Mountain House to the northeast.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Within the park, Highway 1A, also known as the Bow Valley Parkway, loosely parallels Highway 1 between Banff and Lake Louise.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The closest airport with long-haul flights is Calgary International Airport (YYC).
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] There is a registered aerodrome (Banff Aerodrome, (IATA: **YBA**, ICAO: **CYBA**)) operated by Parks Canada located in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The aerodrome requires prior permission for use.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Other transportation facilities within Banff National Park include a Canadian Pacific rail line that generally parallels Highway 1, and Banff Park Compound Heliport.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1978, expansion of Sunshine Village ski resort was approved, with added parking, hotel expansion, and development of Goat's Eye Mountain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Implementation of this development proposal was delayed through the 1980s, while environmental assessments were conducted.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1989, Sunshine Village withdrew its development proposal, in light of government reservations, and submitted a revised proposal in 1992.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] This plan was approved by the government, pending environmental review.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Subsequently, the Canadian Parks and Wilderness Society (CPAWS) filed a court injunction, which halted the development.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] CPAWS also put pressure on UNESCO to revoke Banff's World Heritage Site status, over concerns that developments were harming the park's ecological health.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] While the *National Parks Act* and the 1988 amendment emphasize ecological integrity, in practice Banff has suffered from inconsistent application of the policies.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In 1994, the Banff–Bow Valley Study was mandated by Sheila Copps, the minister responsible for Parks Canada, to provide recommendations on how to better manage human use and development, and maintain ecological integrity.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] While the two-year Banff–Bow Valley Study was underway, development projects were halted, including the expansion of Sunshine Village, and the twinning of the Trans-Canada Highway between Castle Junction and Sunshine.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The panel issued over 500 recommendations, including limiting the growth of the Banff townsite, capping the town's population at 10,000, placing quotas for popular hiking trails, and curtailing development in the park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Another recommendation was to fence off the townsite to reduce confrontations between people and elk.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] The proposed fencing was also intended to reduce access to this refuge for elk from predators, such as wolves that tended to avoid the townsite.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Upon release of the report, Copps immediately moved to accept the proposal to cap the town population.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] She also ordered a small airstrip to be removed, along with a buffalo paddock, and cadet camp, that inhibited wildlife movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] In response to concerns and recommendations raised by the Banff–Bow Valley Study, a number of development plans were curtailed in the 1990s.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Plans to add nine holes at the Banff Springs Golf Resort were withdrawn in 1996.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] With the cap on growth in the town of Banff, Canmore, located just outside the Banff boundary, has been growing rapidly to serve increasing demands of tourists.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-national-park] Major development proposals for Canmore have included the Three Sisters Golf Resorts, proposed in 1992, which has been the subject of contentious debate, with environmental groups arguing that the development would fragment important wildlife corridors in the Bow Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The **Fairmont Banff Springs**, formerly and commonly known as the **Banff Springs Hotel**, is a historic hotel in western Canada, located in Banff, Alberta.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The entire town, including the hotel, is situated in Banff National Park, a national park managed by Parks Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] At an elevation of 1,414 metres (4,640 ft) above sea level, the hotel overlooks a valley towards Mount Rundle, both of which are situated within the Rocky Mountain mountain range.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Opened in 1888 by the Canadian Pacific Railway, it is one of the earliest of Canada's grand railway hotels.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The original five-storey wooden hotel was designed by Bruce Price and was able to accommodate 280 guests.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] With expansions, the original structure became the North Wing, which was eventually destroyed by fire in April 1926.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The present hotel property is made up of several buildings, of which the main hotel consists of a 1914 eleven-storey center tower designed by Walter S.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Painter, and a 1927 North Wing and a 1928 South Wing designed by John Orrock which were built on either side of the Center Tower.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] On 24 June 1988, the hotel buildings were designated as a National Historic Site of Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel property is presently managed by Fairmont Hotels and Resorts.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The Banff Springs Hotel sits at 405 Spray Avenue near the southern boundary of Banff, a resort town within Banff National Park.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel property is bounded by roadways and natural waterways.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Two roadways bound the hotel to the north, Bow River Avenue, and Rundle River Avenue, while Spray Avenue bounds the hotel from the west.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] To the east, the hotel property is bounded by the Spray River.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The river serves as a tributary for the Bow River, a waterway north of the hotel property.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel property sits near the confluence of the two rivers.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The town of Banff is located within the Rocky Mountains mountain range, situated 1,414 metres (4,639 ft) above sea level.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The community itself is built around Tunnel Mountain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel property looks over across the valley towards Mount Rundle.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Other mountain peaks located near the hotel include Cascade Mountain, Mount Norquay, Stoney Squaw Mountain, and Sulphur Mountain.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Given its location within a national park, the hotel is located near a number of attractions and natural landmarks.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] North of the hotel on the Bow River lies Bow Falls.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The Banff Upper Hot Springs is a commercially developed hot spring located south of the hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Banff Springs Hotel is one of Canada's grand railway hotels built by Canadian Pacific Railway.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The present hotel property is made up of two main buildings, an eleven-storey tower, and the main block of the hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Painter, construction for the tower building, or the centre wing, began in 1911, and was completed in 1914.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The main block of the hotel was erected from 1927 to 1928, and replaced the original wooden hotel destroyed in a fire.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The original structure was a five-storey wooden building, able to accommodate 280 guests, was designed by Bruce Price.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] After the original 1888 wooden structure burnt down in 1926, John W.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Orrock, the Chief Engineer for Canadian Pacific Railway, was charged with designing its replacement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The replacement building, or the main block, consisted of the north, and south wing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] As with the tower added in 1911, the replacement structure is made up of a steel frame, clad in Rundle limestone.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Orrock based elements of the new building with the general styles of the original wooden building designed by Price, meaning that the main block also featured elements found on the chateaus of the Loire Valley in France.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] As a result, the main block features massive wall surfaces, and steep copper roofs, dormers, and gables.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The original wooden structure, on which the present north and south wing designs are based, featured architectural elements drawn from Scottish baronial architecture, as well as the chateaus of the Loire Valley.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] This blend of architectural styles would eventually lead to the Châteauesque style used for most of the grand railway hotels in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Châteauesque features found on the building include its steep pitched roofs, pointed dormers, and corner turrets.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] However, contrasting later Châteauesque hotels built in Canada, Banff Springs Hotel's also draws elements from the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Elements from this movement include rounded gables, and rough stone masonry used throughout the building.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The remains of the burnt building were removed in 1926, in order to make way for the north and south wings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The centre wing tower was a large limestone structure, influenced largely by Scottish baronial architecture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The building was designed originally as an extension of the original wooden structure.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Unlike the other wings of the hotel, the centre tower featured almost no French medieval architectural elements.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Painter's designs had windows that were rounded, flat dormers as opposed to pointed ones, and rounded arches rather than pointed arches seen in French Gothic architecture.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The central wing also featured a Renaissance Revival styled arcade before its first floor lounge.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The interior of the hotel features oak beams, oak panellings and linenfolds, animal carvings, plasterwork of the ceilings, terrazzo floors, and stained glasswork.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Materials found in the interior include fossil-filled carved Tyndall limestone from Garson, Manitoba, and Bedford lime flagstones on the floors of Mount Stephen Hall, an event room within the hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The Banff Springs Hotel includes 757 guest rooms and suites spread throughout the hotel property.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel property also houses a number of event spaces, used for conferences, weddings, and other social events.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Event spaces within the hotel building include the Alberta Dining Room, the Alhambra Dining Room, the Cascade Ballroom, Mount Stephen Hall, and the Riverview Walk.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Given its location, the hotel property also features outdoor event spaces, including a terrace garden.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] A number of areas within the hotel property are also occupied by restaurants, or other food-based services.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] As of December 2017, twelve restaurants operate within the hotel property.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Restaurants located within the hotel include *1888 Chop House*, the *Waldhaus*, and the *Rundle Bar*, "Castello".
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The latter restaurant also hosts the hotel's afternoon tea.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel also hosts a locally sourced market, *Stock Food & Drinks*.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Other facilities located on the hotel property include a bowling alley, five turf-topped tennis courts, a swimming pool, and a 27-hole golf course designed by golf course architect Stanley Thompson.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Spa facilities were opened at the hotel in 1991.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The original building was shaped as an H and included an octagonal centre hall, with an additional wing extending from its towards the Bow River.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The building was clad in shingles with stone accents.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Tiered verandahs were situated at the end each wing.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The 1888 structure cost $250,000 and a mistake made by the builder changed the intended orientation of the building, turning its back on the mountain vista.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] This building included more than 100 bedrooms, centered on a five-story, octagonal rotunda.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel was named for the natural hot springs emanating from various places on Sulphur Mountain which was also piped into the hotel.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] An addition in 1902 expanded and renovated the building, adding more than 200 rooms.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] By 1906, plans were advanced for a complete overhaul of the Banff Springs Hotel building, proposing a replacement of much of the original structure.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Walter Painter, chief architect for Canadian Pacific Railway, designed an eleven-story central tower in concrete and stone, flanked by two wings.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] This time correctly oriented to the dramatic view, the so-called "Painter Tower" was completed in 1914 at the cost of $2 million with 300 guest arooms and, for some time, became the tallest building in Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Construction of new wings was delayed by World War I, and the surviving Price wings continued in service.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Further renovations designed by architect, J.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Orrock, who continued in style originated by Painter, significantly expanding the Painter Tower, altering its roofline, and adding two substantial wings following a fire in 1926 which destroyed the original building designed by Price.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The two new wings completed and opened in 1928.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The Monarch of Canada, King George VI, and Queen Elizabeth visited the hotel during their 1939 royal tour of Canada.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] From 1942 to 1945, the hotel was shut down in an effort to free up labour for the war effort.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] In 1968, the building underwent a process of winterization, allowing for the hotel to operate year-round.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel went through several renovations during the latter half of the 20th century, including one in 1971, and another in preparation for the 1988 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] In 2001, Canadian Pacific Hotels, the hotel division of Canadian Pacific Railway, was reorganized as Fairmont Hotels and Resorts, adopting the name from an American company it had purchased in 1999.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] The hotel's name was changed to the Fairmont Banff Springs as a part of this re-branding effort.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] In 2006, seven Fairmont hotels, including Banff Springs, sold to Oxford Properties, a company owned by the Ontario Municipal Employees Retirement System.
[src:banff-springs-hotel/banff-springs-hotel] Fairmont Hotels and Resorts continues to manage the resort following the sale of the hotel property.
